.org/wiki/Fahd"}
{"title_page": "SVT-40", "text_new": "{{Infobox weapon\n|name = SVT-40\n| image = SVT-40 - Ryssland - AM.032865.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n|caption = SVT-40 without magazine from the collections of [[Arm\u00e9museum]], Stockholm, Sweden\n|type = [[Semi-automatic rifle]]/[[battle rifle]]\n|origin = [[Soviet Union]]\n|era = [[World War II]]\n|designer = [[Fedor Tokarev]]\n|design_date = 1938 (updated 1940)<ref name=\"MF\">[http://world.guns.ru/rifle/rfl06-e.htm Modern Firearms article on SVT-40] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031216033834/http://world.guns.ru/rifle/rfl06-e.htm |date=16 December 2003 }}</ref>\n|prod_design_date = 1938\u20131942<ref>\"''\u041a \u0438\u0441\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0443 1942 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a \u0431\u044b\u043b\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0449\u0435\u043d\u043e''\"<br />\u0412.\u041d. \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432. \u041d\u0430\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0443\u043d\u0435 \u0438 \u0432 \u0434\u043d\u0438 \u0438\u0441\u043f\u044b\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439. \u0412\u043e\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f. \u041c., \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442, 1988. \u0441\u0442\u0440.74</ref>\n|serv_design_date = 1940\n|service=1940\u2013present\n|used_by=See ''[[#Users|Users]]''\n|wars={{plainlist|\n* [[Winter War]]\n* [[Continuation War]]\n* [[World War II]]\n* [[Korean War]]\n* [[Vietnam War]]}}\n|spec_type = Self-Loading Rifle\n|caliber = 7.62 mm\n|part_length = {{convert|625|mm|in}}<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n|cartridge = [[7.62\u00d754mmR]]<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n|feed = 10-round detachable [[magazine (firearms)#Box|box magazine]]<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n|action = [[Gas-operated reloading#Short-stroke piston|Gas-operated short-stroke piston]], tilting bolt<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n|rate =\n|velocity = {{convert|830|-|840|m/s|ft/s|abbr=on|sigfig=3}}<ref>\n* [http://www.lonesentry.com/articles/tokarev_m1940/index.html May 1946 (U.S.) Intelligence Bulletin on Tokarev M1940] gives 2720 ft/s\n* \u0421\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d \u0424\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0441\u0435\u0435\u0432, \"\u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430\", ''\u0422\u0435\u0445\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0432\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435'', June 2005, p. 16, gives 840 m/s</ref> (light bullet arr. 1908)\n|weight = {{convert|3.85|kg|lbs}} unloaded<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n|length = {{convert|1226|mm|in}}<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n|variants = SVT-38, SVT-40\n|number = 1,600,000<ref name = \"kehaya\">{{cite book|title = The SKS Carabine (CKC45g)|author = Steve Kehaya|author2=Joe Poyer |year = 1996|publisher = North Cape Publications, Inc.|isbn = 1-882391-14-4|page = 10|edition = 4th}}</ref><ref name = \"ezell\">{{cite book|title= Small Arms of the World: A Basic Manual of Small Arms|author = Edward Clinton Ezell|year = 1983|publisher = Stackpole Books|isbn = 0-8117-1687-2|pages = 894|edition = 12th}}</ref>\n|is_ranged = yes\n|range = {{convert|500|m|yd}}, {{convert|1000|m|yd}}+ (with scope)\n}}\n[[File:RIAN archive 613474 Red Army men attacking.jpg|thumb|Soviet soldiers with SVT-40 rifles.]]\nThe '''SVT-40''' (Samozaryadnaya Vintovka Tokareva, Obrazets 1940 goda, \"Tokarev self-loading rifle, model of 1940\", Russian: \u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430, \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0446 1940 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430, often nicknamed \"''[[Svetlana|Sveta]]''\") is a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[semi-automatic rifle]]. The SVT-40 saw widespread service during and after [[World War II]]. It was intended to be the Soviet Red Army's new [[service rifle]], but its production was disrupted by [[Operation Barbarossa|the German invasion in 1941]], resulting in a change back to the older [[Mosin\u2013Nagant]] bolt-action rifle for the duration of World War II. After the war, the Soviet Union adopted new rifles, such as the [[SKS]] and the [[AK-47]].\n\n== SVT-38 ==\n[[File:SVT-38 - Ryssland - AM.045576.jpg|thumb|left|SVT-38]]\n[[Fedor Tokarev]] created the basic design for the SVT rifle in the early 1930s. Tokarev gave up his previous experiments with recoil-operated self-loading rifles and pursued a gas-operating mechanism instead. Soviet leader [[Joseph Stalin]] had a great interest in semi-automatic infantry rifles, and the army held trials of automatic rifle designs in 1935. The winning rifle was designed by [[Sergei Gavrilovich Simonov]], and was accepted into service the next year as the ''[[AVS-36]]''. However, problems with the AVS quickly became apparent, and both Tokarev and Simonov submitted improved designs to further trials. This time, Tokarev's rifle was accepted for production, under the designation ''SVT-38'' with hopes that it would become the new standard issue rifle of the Red Army. Ambitious production plans anticipated two million rifles per year by 1942. Production began at [[Tula Arms Plant|Tula Arsenal]] in July 1939 (production at [[Izhmash]] began in late 1939).<ref name=\"nuggets\">[http://www.mosinnagant.net/USSR/svt401.asp The Red Army's Self Loading Rifles: A Brief History Of The Tokarev Rifles Models of 1938 and 1940. By Vic Thomas Of Michigan Historical Collectables]</ref>\n\nThe SVT-38 is a [[Gas-operated reloading|gas-operated]] rifle with a short-stroke, spring-loaded piston above the barrel and a [[tilting bolt]].<ref name=\"MF\"/> This configuration gained wider acceptance later. There is some dispute about who exactly first developed this operating principle, as the SVT's mechanism (as implemented in 1935 competition prototype) closely resembles [[Dieudonn\u00e9 Saive]]'s design of 1937; Saive eventually designed both the [[FN-49]] and [[FN FAL]], which use similar operating principles.\n\nSoviet small arms were usually of simple and robust construction, designed for use by poorly educated and sometimes poorly equipped soldiers. The SVT-38, in contrast, had been designed with weight-saving in mind, including its wood stock, receiver, and action. It was a gas-operated action with a gas-cylinder cup that was not readily accessible. It was complex by Soviet standards, and was not suited to handle corrosively-primed ammunition without frequent cleaning.<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n\nThe SVT-38 was equipped with a [[bayonet]] and a 10-round detachable [[Magazine (firearms)|magazine]]. The receiver was open-top, which enabled reloading of the magazine using five-round Mosin\u2013Nagant [[stripper clip]]s. Fairly advanced features for the time were the adjustable gas system, [[muzzle brake]], and [[telescopic sight]] rails milled into the receiver. The sniper variant had an additional locking notch for a see-through scope mount and was equipped with a 3.5\u00d7 [[PU scope|PU telescopic sight]]. This instrument was slightly shorter than the otherwise-similar PU scope used on the Mosin\u2013Nagant M1891/30 sniper rifle.\n\n==SVT-40 and its derivatives==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-198-1394-18A, Russland, Soldat mit russischem Gewehr.jpg|thumb|A German soldier firing a captured SVT-40]]\n[[File:1940 Tula SVT40.jpg|thumb|SVT-40]]\nThe SVT-38 saw its combat debut in the 1939\u20131940 [[Winter War]] with Finland. The initial reaction of the troops to this new rifle was negative. Among the criticisms were the rifle being too long and cumbersome, difficult to maintain and the magazine tending to fall out. Production of the SVT-38 was terminated in April 1940 after some 150,000 examples had been manufactured. An improved design, the ''SVT-40'', entered production. It was a more refined, lighter design incorporating a modified, folding, magazine release. The hand guard was now of one-piece construction and the cleaning rod was housed under the barrel. Other changes were made to simplify manufacturing. Production of the improved version began in July 1940 at Tula and later at factories in Izhevsk and Podolsk. Production of the Mosin\u2013Nagant M1891/30 bolt-action rifle continued and it remained the standard-issue rifle to Red Army troops, with the SVT-40 more often issued to non-commissioned officers and elite units like the naval infantry. Since these factories already had experience manufacturing the SVT-38, output increased quickly and an estimated 70,000 SVT-40s were produced in 1940.\n\nBy the time of [[Operation Barbarossa]], the German invasion of the USSR in June 1941, the SVT-40 was already in widespread use by the Red Army. In a Soviet infantry division's [[table of organization and equipment]], one-third of rifles were supposed to be SVTs, though in practice they seldom achieved this ratio. The first months of the war were disastrous for the Soviet Union; they lost hundreds of thousands of SVT-40s. To make up for this, production of the Mosin\u2013Nagant rifles was reintroduced. In contrast, the SVT was more difficult to manufacture, and troops with only rudimentary training had difficulty maintaining it. [[Submachine gun]]s like the [[PPSh-41]] had proven their value as simple, cheap and effective weapons to supplement infantry firepower. This led to a gradual decline in SVT production. In 1941, over one million SVTs were produced but in 1942 Ishevsk arsenal was ordered to cease SVT production and switch back to the Mosin\u2013Nagant 91/30. Only 264,000 SVTs were manufactured in 1942 and production continued to diminish until the order to cease production was finally given in January 1945. Total production of the SVT-38/40 was around 1,600,000 rifles, of which 51,710 were the SVT-40 sniper variant.<ref name=\"MF\"/><ref name = \"kehaya\"/><ref name = \"ezell\"/>\n\n[[File:1941 Tula SVT-40 in Original Sniper Configuration.jpg|thumb|A 1941 Tula SVT-40 in original sniper configuration]]\n\nSVTs frequently suffered from vertical shot dispersion; the army reported that the rifles were of \"flimsy construction and there were difficulties experienced in their repair and maintenance\".<ref>Small Arms of the World by W. H. B. Smith 9th Edition Revised by Joseph E. Smith 1969 p.&nbsp;583</ref> The stock, made of Arctic Birch, was prone to cracking in the wrist from recoil. This was generally remedied by drilling and inserting one or two large industrial bolts horizontally into the stock just before the wrist meets the receiver.<ref>[https://www.milsurps.com/showthread.php?t=63516&p=422787&viewfull=1#post422787 SVT-40 stock crack/bubba questions? - Post #5]</ref><ref>[https://www.reddit.com/r/canadaguns/comments/a50wnt/svt40_stock_repair_and_reinforcing_screw/ Svt-40 stock repair and reinforcing screw]</ref> Many rifles were also poorly seated in their stocks, letting the receiver shift on firing. This led to a field modification that selectively [[Rifle bedding|shimmed the stock]] with birch chips, usually around the receiver and in between where the wood stock meets the lower metal handguard.<ref>[https://forums.gunboards.com/showthread.php?362417-How-were-SVT-s-quot-bedded-quot How were SVT's \"bedded\"?]</ref> For a sniper rifle, this was unacceptable and production of the specialized sniper variant of the SVT was terminated in 1942.<ref name=\"MF\"/> Milling scope rails in the receivers of standard SVT rifles was also discontinued. Other production changes included a new, simpler muzzle brake design with two vents per-side instead of the six on the original.\n\n=== AVT-40 automatic rifle ===\nTo supplement the Red Army's shortage of [[machine gun]]s, an SVT version capable of full-automatic fire (designated the ''AVT-40'') was ordered into production on 20 May 1942; the first batches reached the troops in July.<ref name=\"Bolotin1995_111\"/> It was externally similar to the SVT, but its modified safety also acted as a fire selector allowing for both semi-automatic and fully automatic fire modes. When fired automatically the rifle had a rate of fire of approximately 750 RPM, faster than even the [[DP machine gun]] which fired the same cartridge at 550 RPM. To better resist the stress of automatic fire, the AVT featured a slightly stouter stock made of hardwood usually distinguished with a large \u201cA\u201d engraved in it; surplus AVT stocks were later used on refurbished SVTs. In service, the AVT proved a disappointment: automatic fire was largely uncontrollable, and the rifles often suffered breakages under the increased strain.(Documents discovered after the war indicated that during testing, under continuous Full Auto fire, an AVT-40's barrel would be \"shot out\", meaning the rifling in the barrel would be completely worn down, in as little as 200-250 rounds.) The use of the AVT's automatic fire mode was subsequently prohibited, and production of the rifle was relatively brief; none were made after the summer of 1943.<ref name=\"Bolotin1995_111\">{{cite book|first=David Naumovich |last=Bolotin |others=trans. Igor F. Naftul'eff |editor1-first=John |editor1-last=Walter |editor2-first=Heikki |editor2-last=Pohjolainen] |title=Soviet Small-arms and Ammunition |year=1995 |publisher=Finnish Arms Museum Foundation (Suomen asemuseos\u00e4\u00e4ti\u00f6) |location=Hyvink\u00e4\u00e4 |isbn=9519718419|page=111}}</ref>\n\nA shorter carbine version ''SKT-40'' ('''\u0421\u041a\u0422-40''') was designed in 1940 and was submitted to a competitive test with a design of Simonov in the same year; neither was accepted for service.<ref name=\"Bolotin1995_112\">{{cite book|first=David Naumovich |last=Bolotin |others=trans. Igor F. Naftul'eff |editor1-first=John |editor1-last=Walter |editor2-first=Heikki |editor2-last=Pohjolainen] |title=Soviet Small-arms and Ammunition |year=1995 |publisher=Finnish Arms Museum Foundation (Suomen asemuseos\u00e4\u00e4ti\u00f6) |location=Hyvink\u00e4\u00e4 |isbn=9519718419 |page=112}}</ref> It was reportedly produced in small numbers; but this has been disputed.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}} Later, a prototype version chambered for the new, shorter, [[7.62\u00d739mm]] round was developed, but was not accepted for production.<ref name=\"Bolotin1995_111\"/> An [[assault rifle]] based on a scaled down SVT with [[7.62x41mm]] chambering called the '''AT-44''' was also put into development, competing with the [[AS-44]] design. It failed to be accepted for similar reliability issues as the AVT.<ref>[https://raigap.livejournal.com/359121.html \u041e\u043f\u044b\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0430\u0432\u0442\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0442 \u0422\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430 \u0410\u0422-44 (\u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420. 1944 \u0433\u043e\u0434)]</ref> A [[Silencer (firearms)|silenced]] variation was also experimented with, though too ended in failure.<ref>[https://survival.com.ua/razvitie-glushiteley-zvuka-vyistrela-ustroystvo-glushitelya-vintovki-svt-40-karabina-mauzer-98/ \u0420\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0433\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u0437\u0432\u0443\u043a\u0430 \u0432\u044b\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0430, \u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0433\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0438 \u0421\u0412\u0422-40, \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0431\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0440-98\u041a \u0438 \u043f\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430-\u043f\u0443\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0418\u043d\u0433\u0440\u044d\u043c]</ref><ref>[https://www.kalashnikov.ru/medialibrary/1a2/pbs.pdf \u0412 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0434\u0430\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0442\u0435\u043c\u044b \u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0443\u0435\u043c \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b \u043e\u0431]</ref>\n\nAccording to certain documents (namely AVT related) and very few rare pictures, they appear to have played around with the idea of a 15-round extended magazine. No physical examples have been found however, leading to the common assumption that it was a failure (much like the AVS-36's 15-round mag). Quite a few pictures have been observed of non-Soviets (namely Germans and Finns) using SVT-38s and 40s with what appear to be [[Bren]] or [[Lahti-Saloranta M/26|LS/26]] magazines. Very little is known about usage with the unsupported magazines (including their reliability and max capacity).\n\n==SVTs outside of the Soviet Union==\nThe first country outside the Soviet Union to employ the SVT was Finland, which captured some 2,700 SVT-38s during the [[Winter War]], and over 15,000 SVTs during the [[Continuation War]]. The SVT saw extensive use in Finnish hands.<ref name=\"Finland\">{{cite book|title=Finland at War 1939\u201345|series=Elite 141|first1=Philip |last1=Jowett|first2= Brent|last2= Snodgrass|date= 5 Jul 2006|isbn=9781841769691|publisher=Osprey Publishing|page=48}}</ref> The Finns even attempted to make their own clone of the SVT-38 designated ''Tapako'', though only a prototype was ever conceived.<ref name=\"Jaeger\"/> The Finns would continue to experiment with producing their own SVT based rifles until the late 50s with the introduction of the [[RK-62]]. Germany captured hundreds of thousands of SVTs from the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]]. As the Germans were short of self-loading rifles themselves, SVT-38 and 40s, designated respectively as '''Selbstladegewehr 258(r)''' and '''Selbstladegewehr 259(r)''' by the [[Wehrmacht]], saw widespread use in German hands against their former owners. Study of the SVT's gas-operated action also aided in the development of the German [[Gewehr 43]] rifle.<ref name=\"Bishop1998\">{{cite encyclopedia|title=Tokarev rifles|encyclopedia=The encyclopedia of weapons of World War II|pages=218\u2013219|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Encyclopedia_of_Weapons_of_World_War.html?id=MuGsf0psjvcC|isbn= 9780760710227|editor-first=Chris|editor-last=Bishop|publisher=Barnes & Noble|year=1998}}</ref>\nDuring the 1940s, [[Switzerland]] began looking into equipping its military with semi-auto rifles. Although never officially adopted, [[W+F Bern]] produced an almost faithful clone of the SVT with [[7.5 mm Swiss]] chambering and a 6 round magazine called the '''AK44'''.<ref>[https://www.forgottenweapons.com/ria-prototype-wf-bern-ak44-copy-of-the-svt/ RIA: Prototype W+F Bern AK44 Copy of the SVT]</ref>\n\n==Post-war==\nAfter the war, SVTs were mostly withdrawn from service and refurbished in arsenals, then stored. In Soviet service, firearms like the [[SKS]] and the [[AK-47]] as well as the later [[Dragunov sniper rifle|SVD]] made the SVT obsolete, and the rifle was generally out of service by 1955.{{cn|date=February 2019}} Only a few SVTs were exported to Soviet allies and clients. The [[Korean People's Army]] reportedly received some before the [[Korean War]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=North Korean Small Arms (Democratic People's Republic of Korea)|magazine=Small Arms Review |volume=16|issue=2 |date=June 2012|url=https://smallarmsreview.com/display.article.cfm?idarticles=1108}}</ref><ref name=\"Korea\">{{cite book|title=Korean War Almanac|first=Paul M.|last=Edwards|isbn=0-8160-6037-1|publisher=Facts On File|chapter=Communist weapons, infantry|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816060375/page/498 498-499]|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5gYCm0bM68sC&q=SVT|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816060375/page/498|year=2006}}</ref> The Finnish Army retired the SVT in 1958, and about 7,500 rifles were sold to the United States civilian market through firearm importer [[Interarms]]. This marked the end of SVTs in regular service.\n\nIn the Soviet Union, some SVTs (without bayonets) were sold as civilian hunting rifles<ref>\u041c. \u0411\u043b\u044e\u043c, \u0410. \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043d\u043e\u0432. \u041e\u0445\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0443 \u043e \u0421\u0412\u0422 // \u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b \"\u041e\u0445\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0438 \u043e\u0445\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0447\u044c\u0435 \u0445\u043e\u0437\u044f\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\", \u2116 11, 1989</ref>, although other SVTs were kept in storage until the 1990s, when many rifles were sold abroad, along with other surplus military firearms.\n\nCurrently the SVT is fairly widely available for collectors and historical enthusiasts, and is highly sought after. In Russia, limited examples for civilian use have been sold as the \u041e\u0421\u041a-88 (OSK 88) and [[Molot]] KO-SVT with some variations in stock, barrel length and optics. The rifle's popularity is due to a combination of the inexpensive nature of its [[7.62\u00d754mmR]] ammunition, favorable [[aesthetics]], historical significance, and pleasant shooting characteristics.{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n\nDespite its relatively brief service career, the SVT was a prolific rifle on the Eastern Front during World War II, and it had considerable impact on European battle rifle designs during and immediately after the war. The German [[Gewehr 43|G-43]] was influenced by the SVT in its design, as was Simonov's experimental carbine during the closing stages of the war (which would later become the [[SKS]]). The [[FN FAL]] and its ancestor [[FN Model 1949|FN-49]] employ the same locking mechanism and operating principle as the SVT, although as mentioned above, this is most likely coincidental. As a service rifle, the SVT had its problems, but so did contemporary semi-automatic rifles made by other countries. The main reason for the gradual downfall of SVT usage in combat was not its technical disadvantages; rather, the reason was that, with the immense, continual demand for rifles in the front lines, Soviet factories could produce other, simpler designs in far greater quantities in the same length of time it took to produce the SVT. In 1944 the Soviet Union adopted the [[7.62x39]] round used in the RPD Light Machinegun, SKS, and AK-47 Rifles. In 1945 the [[SKS]] was adopted which replaced the SVT-40 as the main infantry rifle, which itself was replaced by the AK-47 in 1948.\n\n==Users==\n* {{flag|Independent State of Croatia|name=Croatia}}<ref>{{cite book|title=World War II Croation Legionaries: Croation Troops Under Axis Command 1941\u201445|author=Vladimir Brnardic|isbn=978-1-4728-1767-9|page=9|date=22 November 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Czechoslovakia}}: [[1st Czechoslovak Army Corps in the USSR|1st Czechoslovak Independent Brigade in the USSR]]<ref>{{cite web|title=1st Czechoslovak Independent Brigade|url=https://www.czechpatriots.com/en/1st-czechoslovak-independent-brigade.php|website=czechpatriots.com|first=Michal|last= Gelbi\u010d|access-date=3 February 2019}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Estonia}} [[Forest Brothers|Estonian partisans]] after World War 2<ref>{{cite book|title= Germany's Eastern Front Allies (2): Baltic Forces|series=Men-at-Arms 363|last1=Nigel|first1= Thomas|first2=Carlos |last2=Caballero Jurado|date= 25 Jan 2002|isbn=9781841761930|page=40|publisher=Osprey Publishing|ref=harv}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Finland}}: Captured from Soviet troops, AVT-40 version also used.<ref name=\"Jaeger\">{{cite web|first=|last=|title=Rifles, part 4 |date=15 January 2017 |url=https://www.jaegerplatoon.net/RIFLES4.htm}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|East Germany}} [[East Germany|German Democratic Republic]] after WWII, issued as the '''SWT'''<ref>[https://www.tankograd.com/cms/website.php?id=/en/Fahrzeuge-und-Waffen-der-Nationalen-Volksarmee-3.htm Military and Paramilitary Vehicles and Weapons of East Germany]</ref>\n* {{flag|Georgia}}<ref name ='SAS 1998 4'>{{cite book|url=http://www.smallarmssurvey.org/fileadmin/docs/B-Occasional-papers/SAS-OP06-Georgia.pdf|chapter-url=|chapter=|title=Politics From The Barrel of a Gun|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=1998|author=Small Arms Survey|pages=40|isbn=|author-link=Small Arms Survey}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Lithuania}}: Lithuanian civil Police used captured SVT-40s during the [[German occupation of Lithuania during World War II|German occupation]].{{sfn|Nigel|Caballero Jurado|2002|p=46}}\n* {{flag|Nazi Germany}} (Captured from Soviet troops)<ref>{{cite book|title=Desperate Measures: The Last-Ditch Weapons of the Nazi Volkssturm|page=61|author=W. Darrin Weaver|year=2005|publisher=Collector Grade Publications|isbn=0889353727}}</ref>\n* {{flag|North Korea}}\n* {{flagicon|Hungary}} [[People's Republic of Hungary]]{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n* {{flag|Poland}}: [[Polish Armed Forces in the East]]<ref name=\"mcnab2002\">{{cite book |last=McNab |first=Chris|title=20th Century Military Uniforms |year=2002 |edition=2nd |publisher=Grange Books |location=Kent |isbn=1-84013-476-3|page=191}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Romania}} [[Socialist Republic of Romania|People's Republic of Romania]]{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n* {{flag|Soviet Union}}\n* {{flag|Switzerland}} (AK-44 clone)\n* {{flag|Ukraine}}: 11,500 stored in 2008<ref>{{cite web|lang=uk|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0434\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0443 \u0432\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u0430\u0439\u043d\u0430 \u0417\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b, \u044f\u043a\u0435 \u043c\u043e\u0436\u0435 \u0431\u0443\u0442\u0438 \u0432\u0456\u0434\u0447\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043e|url=https://zakon4.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/1092-2008-%D1%80|website=zakon4.rada.gov.ua|date=6 August 2008|trans-title=On Approval of the List of Military Property of the Armed Forces, which may be alienated}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Vietnam}}: limited service.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Chien Cu-War Material|page=9|author=Nguyen-Khanh Maj. Gen. & Tran-Van-Minh Maj. Gen.|year=1964}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Chicom Series|page=106|author=Granville N Rideout|year=1971|edition=1st|publisher=Yankee Pub. Co}}</ref><ref>[https://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2014/11/17/strange-guns-viet-cong-svt-40/ Strange Guns: Viet-Cong SVT-40]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[AVS-36]]\n* [[FG 42]]\n* [[Gewehr 43]]\n* [[M1 Garand]]\n* [[M1941 Johnson rifle]]\n* [[SKS]]\n* [[List of Russian weaponry]]\n* [[Lyudmila Pavlichenko]]\n\n== Museum exhibits ==\n* One SVT-38 rifle, one SVT-40 rifle and one SKT-40 carbine are in collection of Tula State Arms Museum in [[Tula Kremlin]]<ref>\"''\u041a\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0439 \u0424. \u0412. \u0422\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u044b\u043c \u043e\u043f\u044b\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0446\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0438\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0445 \u0441 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u0448\u0442\u0430\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0446\u0430 1938 \u0433. \u0438 1940 \u0433. \u0432 \u043a\u043e\u043b\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0435\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0435, \u0438\u043c\u0435\u044e\u0449\u0435\u0435 \u043c\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435. ... \u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0431\u0438\u043d \u0422\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430 \u0421\u041a\u0422-40, \u0440\u0435\u0434\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044f\u0448\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u0435\u043d\u044c \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0446, \u0431\u044b\u043b \u043b\u0438\u0447\u043d\u044b\u043c \u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0435\u043c \u0412. \u0413. \u0416\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430, \u0441\u0435\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044f \u0422\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0412\u041a\u041f (\u0431), \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0422\u0443\u043b\u044b \u043e\u0441\u0435\u043d\u044c\u044e 1941 \u0433.''\"<br />[http://www.museum-arms.ru/collections/automat-battlearms/ \u041e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0435 \u0431\u043e\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0435 \u0430\u0432\u0442\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435] / \u043e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u0422\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u044f \u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u044f</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|SVT-40}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20031216033834/http://world.guns.ru/rifle/rfl06-e.htm History and technicalities of the SVT-40]\n* [http://www.mosinnagant.net/USSR/SVTsection.asp SVT info and pictures at Mosin-Nagant.net, compiled by Vic Thomas]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091113091311/http://50ae.net/collection/svt40/ SVT-40 Pictorial]\n* [http://www.kalashnikov.ru/upload/medialibrary/3fb/50_56.pdf \u0421\u0412\u0422 \u0442\u0440\u0443\u0434\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u0443\u0434\u044c\u0431\u0430], Kalashnikov magazine, 2001/6, pp.&nbsp;50\u201356\n* [https://forums.gunboards.com/showthread.php?504617-Tokarev-SVT-40-Identifying-collecting-and-FAQ Tokarev SVT-40. Identifying, collecting and FAQ]\n\n{{WWIIUSSRInfWeapons}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:7.62\u00d754mmR battle rifles]] <!-- AVT-40 variant -->\n[[Category:7.62\u00d754mmR semi-automatic rifles]]\n[[Category:Short stroke piston firearms]]\n[[Category:Tula Arms Plant products]]\n[[Category:Semi-automatic rifles of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:World War II battle rifles]]\n[[Category:World War II semi-automatic rifles]]\n[[Category:World War II infantry weapons of the Soviet Union]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox weapon\n|name = SVT-40\n| image = SVT-40 - Ryssland - AM.032865.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n|caption = SVT-40 without magazine from the collections of [[Arm\u00e9museum]], Stockholm, Sweden\n|type = [[Semi-automatic rifle]]/[[battle rifle]]\n|origin = [[Soviet Union]]\n|era = [[World War II]]\n|designer = [[Fedor Tokarev]]\n|design_date = 1938 (updated 1940)<ref name=\"MF\">[http://world.guns.ru/rifle/rfl06-e.htm Modern Firearms article on SVT-40] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031216033834/http://world.guns.ru/rifle/rfl06-e.htm |date=16 December 2003 }}</ref>\n|prod_design_date = 1938\u20131942<ref>\"''\u041a \u0438\u0441\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0443 1942 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a \u0431\u044b\u043b\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0449\u0435\u043d\u043e''\"<br />\u0412.\u041d. \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432. \u041d\u0430\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0443\u043d\u0435 \u0438 \u0432 \u0434\u043d\u0438 \u0438\u0441\u043f\u044b\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439. \u0412\u043e\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f. \u041c., \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442, 1988. \u0441\u0442\u0440.74</ref>\n|serv_design_date = 1940\n|service=1940\u2013present\n|used_by=See ''[[#Users|Users]]''\n|wars={{plainlist|\n* [[Winter War]]\n* [[Continuation War]]\n* [[World War II]]\n* [[Korean War]]\n* [[Vietnam War]]}}\n|spec_type = Self-Loading Rifle\n|caliber = 7.62 mm\n|part_length = {{convert|625|mm|in}}<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n|cartridge = [[7.62\u00d754mmR]]<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n|feed = 10-round detachable [[magazine (firearms)#Box|box magazine]]<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n|action = [[Gas-operated reloading#Short-stroke piston|Gas-operated short-stroke piston]], tilting bolt<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n|rate =\n|velocity = {{convert|830|-|840|m/s|ft/s|abbr=on|sigfig=3}}<ref>\n* [http://www.lonesentry.com/articles/tokarev_m1940/index.html May 1946 (U.S.) Intelligence Bulletin on Tokarev M1940] gives 2720 ft/s\n* \u0421\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d \u0424\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0441\u0435\u0435\u0432, \"\u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430\", ''\u0422\u0435\u0445\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0432\u043e\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435'', June 2005, p. 16, gives 840 m/s</ref> (light bullet arr. 1908)\n|weight = {{convert|3.85|kg|lbs}} unloaded<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n|length = {{convert|1226|mm|in}}<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n|variants = SVT-38, SVT-40\n|number = 1,600,000<ref name = \"kehaya\">{{cite book|title = The SKS Carabine (CKC45g)|author = Steve Kehaya|author2=Joe Poyer |year = 1996|publisher = North Cape Publications, Inc.|isbn = 1-882391-14-4|page = 10|edition = 4th}}</ref><ref name = \"ezell\">{{cite book|title= Small Arms of the World: A Basic Manual of Small Arms|author = Edward Clinton Ezell|year = 1983|publisher = Stackpole Books|isbn = 0-8117-1687-2|pages = 894|edition = 12th}}</ref>\n|is_ranged = yes\n|range = {{convert|500|m|yd}}, {{convert|1000|m|yd}}+ (with scope)\n}}\n[[File:RIAN archive 613474 Red Army men attacking.jpg|thumb|Soviet soldiers with SVT-40 rifles.]]\nThe '''SVT-40''' (Samozaryadnaya Vintovka Tokareva, Obrazets 1940 goda, \"Tokarev self-loading rifle, model of 1940\", Russian: \u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430, \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0446 1940 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430, often nicknamed \"''[[Svetlana|Sveta]]''\") is a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[semi-automatic rifle]]. The SVT-40 saw widespread service during and after [[World War II]]. It was intended to be the Soviet Red Army's new [[service rifle]], but its production was disrupted by [[Operation Barbarossa|the German invasion in 1941]], resulting in a change back to the older [[Mosin\u2013Nagant]] bolt-action rifle for the duration of World War II. After the war, the Soviet Union adopted new rifles, such as the [[SKS]] and the [[AK-47]].\n\n== SVT-38 ==\n[[File:SVT-38 - Ryssland - AM.045576.jpg|thumb|left|SVT-38]]\n[[Fedor Tokarev]] created the basic design for the SVT rifle in the early 1930s. Tokarev gave up his previous experiments with recoil-operated self-loading rifles and pursued a gas-operating mechanism instead. Soviet leader [[Joseph Stalin]] had a great interest in semi-automatic infantry rifles, and the army held trials of automatic rifle designs in 1935. The winning rifle was designed by [[Sergei Gavrilovich Simonov]], and was accepted into service the next year as the ''[[AVS-36]]''. However, problems with the AVS quickly became apparent, and both Tokarev and Simonov submitted improved designs to further trials. This time, Tokarev's rifle was accepted for production, under the designation ''SVT-38'' with hopes that it would become the new standard issue rifle of the Red Army. Ambitious production plans anticipated two million rifles per year by 1942. Production began at [[Tula Arms Plant|Tula Arsenal]] in July 1939 (production at [[Izhmash]] began in late 1939).<ref name=\"nuggets\">[http://www.mosinnagant.net/USSR/svt401.asp The Red Army's Self Loading Rifles: A Brief History Of The Tokarev Rifles Models of 1938 and 1940. By Vic Thomas Of Michigan Historical Collectables]</ref>\n\nThe SVT-38 is a [[Gas-operated reloading|gas-operated]] rifle with a short-stroke, spring-loaded piston above the barrel and a [[tilting bolt]].<ref name=\"MF\"/> This configuration gained wider acceptance later. There is some dispute about who exactly first developed this operating principle, as the SVT's mechanism (as implemented in 1935 competition prototype) closely resembles [[Dieudonn\u00e9 Saive]]'s design of 1937; Saive eventually designed both the [[FN-49]] and [[FN FAL]], which use similar operating principles.\n\nSoviet small arms were usually of simple and robust construction, designed for use by poorly educated and sometimes poorly equipped soldiers. The SVT-38, in contrast, had been designed with weight-saving in mind, including its wood stock, receiver, and action. It was a gas-operated action with a gas-cylinder cup that was not readily accessible. It was complex by Soviet standards, and was not suited to handle corrosively-primed ammunition without frequent cleaning.<ref name=\"MF\"/>\n\nThe SVT-38 was equipped with a [[bayonet]] and a 10-round detachable [[Magazine (firearms)|magazine]]. The receiver was open-top, which enabled reloading of the magazine using five-round Mosin\u2013Nagant [[stripper clip]]s. Fairly advanced features for the time were the adjustable gas system, [[muzzle brake]], and [[telescopic sight]] rails milled into the receiver. The sniper variant had an additional locking notch for a see-through scope mount and was equipped with a 3.5\u00d7 [[PU scope|PU telescopic sight]]. This instrument was slightly shorter than the otherwise-similar PU scope used on the Mosin\u2013Nagant M1891/30 sniper rifle.\n\n==SVT-40 and its derivatives==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 101I-198-1394-18A, Russland, Soldat mit russischem Gewehr.jpg|thumb|A German soldier firing a captured SVT-40]]\n[[File:1940 Tula SVT40.jpg|thumb|SVT-40]]\nThe SVT-38 saw its combat debut in the 1939\u20131940 [[Winter War]] with Finland. The initial reaction of the troops to this new rifle was negative. Among the criticisms were the rifle being too long and cumbersome, difficult to maintain and the magazine tending to fall out. Production of the SVT-38 was terminated in April 1940 after some 150,000 examples had been manufactured. An improved design, the ''SVT-40'', entered production. It was a more refined, lighter design incorporating a modified, folding, magazine release. The hand guard was now of one-piece construction and the cleaning rod was housed under the barrel. Other changes were made to simplify manufacturing. Production of the improved version began in July 1940 at Tula and later at factories in Izhevsk and Podolsk. Production of the Mosin\u2013Nagant M1891/30 bolt-action rifle continued and it remained the standard-issue rifle to Red Army troops, with the SVT-40 more often issued to non-commissioned officers and elite units like the naval infantry. Since these factories already had experience manufacturing the SVT-38, output increased quickly and an estimated 70,000 SVT-40s were produced in 1940.\n\nBy the time the [[Operation Barbarossa]], the German invasion of the USSR in June 1941, the SVT-40 was already in widespread use by the Red Army. In a Soviet infantry division's [[table of organization and equipment]], one-third of rifles were supposed to be SVTs, though in practice they seldom achieved this ratio. The first months of the war were disastrous for the Soviet Union; they lost hundreds of thousands of SVT-40s. To make up for this, production of the Mosin\u2013Nagant rifles was reintroduced. In contrast, the SVT was more difficult to manufacture, and troops with only rudimentary training had difficulty maintaining it. [[Submachine gun]]s like the [[PPSh-41]] had proven their value as simple, cheap and effective weapons to supplement infantry firepower. This led to a gradual decline in SVT production. In 1941, over one million SVTs were produced but in 1942 Ishevsk arsenal was ordered to cease SVT production and switch back to the Mosin\u2013Nagant 91/30. Only 264,000 SVTs were manufactured in 1942 and production continued to diminish until the order to cease production was finally given in January 1945. Total production of the SVT-38/40 was around 1,600,000 rifles, of which 51,710 were the SVT-40 sniper variant.<ref name=\"MF\"/><ref name = \"kehaya\"/><ref name = \"ezell\"/>\n\n[[File:1941 Tula SVT-40 in Original Sniper Configuration.jpg|thumb|A 1941 Tula SVT-40 in original sniper configuration]]\n\nSVTs frequently suffered from vertical shot dispersion; the army reported that the rifles were of \"flimsy construction and there were difficulties experienced in their repair and maintenance\".<ref>Small Arms of the World by W. H. B. Smith 9th Edition Revised by Joseph E. Smith 1969 p.&nbsp;583</ref> The stock, made of Arctic Birch, was prone to cracking in the wrist from recoil. This was generally remedied by drilling and inserting one or two large industrial bolts horizontally into the stock just before the wrist meets the receiver.<ref>[https://www.milsurps.com/showthread.php?t=63516&p=422787&viewfull=1#post422787 SVT-40 stock crack/bubba questions? - Post #5]</ref><ref>[https://www.reddit.com/r/canadaguns/comments/a50wnt/svt40_stock_repair_and_reinforcing_screw/ Svt-40 stock repair and reinforcing screw]</ref> Many rifles were also poorly seated in their stocks, letting the receiver shift on firing. This led to a field modification that selectively [[Rifle bedding|shimmed the stock]] with birch chips, usually around the receiver and in between where the wood stock meets the lower metal handguard.<ref>[https://forums.gunboards.com/showthread.php?362417-How-were-SVT-s-quot-bedded-quot How were SVT's \"bedded\"?]</ref> For a sniper rifle, this was unacceptable and production of the specialized sniper variant of the SVT was terminated in 1942.<ref name=\"MF\"/> Milling scope rails in the receivers of standard SVT rifles was also discontinued. Other production changes included a new, simpler muzzle brake design with two vents per-side instead of the six on the original.\n\n=== AVT-40 automatic rifle ===\nTo supplement the Red Army's shortage of [[machine gun]]s, an SVT version capable of full-automatic fire (designated the ''AVT-40'') was ordered into production on 20 May 1942; the first batches reached the troops in July.<ref name=\"Bolotin1995_111\"/> It was externally similar to the SVT, but its modified safety also acted as a fire selector allowing for both semi-automatic and fully automatic fire modes. When fired automatically the rifle had a rate of fire of approximately 750 RPM, faster than even the [[DP machine gun]] which fired the same cartridge at 550 RPM. To better resist the stress of automatic fire, the AVT featured a slightly stouter stock made of hardwood usually distinguished with a large \u201cA\u201d engraved in it; surplus AVT stocks were later used on refurbished SVTs. In service, the AVT proved a disappointment: automatic fire was largely uncontrollable, and the rifles often suffered breakages under the increased strain.(Documents discovered after the war indicated that during testing, under continuous Full Auto fire, an AVT-40's barrel would be \"shot out\", meaning the rifling in the barrel would be completely worn down, in as little as 200-250 rounds.) The use of the AVT's automatic fire mode was subsequently prohibited, and production of the rifle was relatively brief; none were made after the summer of 1943.<ref name=\"Bolotin1995_111\">{{cite book|first=David Naumovich |last=Bolotin |others=trans. Igor F. Naftul'eff |editor1-first=John |editor1-last=Walter |editor2-first=Heikki |editor2-last=Pohjolainen] |title=Soviet Small-arms and Ammunition |year=1995 |publisher=Finnish Arms Museum Foundation (Suomen asemuseos\u00e4\u00e4ti\u00f6) |location=Hyvink\u00e4\u00e4 |isbn=9519718419|page=111}}</ref>\n\nA shorter carbine version ''SKT-40'' ('''\u0421\u041a\u0422-40''') was designed in 1940 and was submitted to a competitive test with a design of Simonov in the same year; neither was accepted for service.<ref name=\"Bolotin1995_112\">{{cite book|first=David Naumovich |last=Bolotin |others=trans. Igor F. Naftul'eff |editor1-first=John |editor1-last=Walter |editor2-first=Heikki |editor2-last=Pohjolainen] |title=Soviet Small-arms and Ammunition |year=1995 |publisher=Finnish Arms Museum Foundation (Suomen asemuseos\u00e4\u00e4ti\u00f6) |location=Hyvink\u00e4\u00e4 |isbn=9519718419 |page=112}}</ref> It was reportedly produced in small numbers; but this has been disputed.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}} Later, a prototype version chambered for the new, shorter, [[7.62\u00d739mm]] round was developed, but was not accepted for production.<ref name=\"Bolotin1995_111\"/> An [[assault rifle]] based on a scaled down SVT with [[7.62x41mm]] chambering called the '''AT-44''' was also put into development, competing with the [[AS-44]] design. It failed to be accepted for similar reliability issues as the AVT.<ref>[https://raigap.livejournal.com/359121.html \u041e\u043f\u044b\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0430\u0432\u0442\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0442 \u0422\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430 \u0410\u0422-44 (\u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420. 1944 \u0433\u043e\u0434)]</ref> A [[Silencer (firearms)|silenced]] variation was also experimented with, though too ended in failure.<ref>[https://survival.com.ua/razvitie-glushiteley-zvuka-vyistrela-ustroystvo-glushitelya-vintovki-svt-40-karabina-mauzer-98/ \u0420\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0433\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u0437\u0432\u0443\u043a\u0430 \u0432\u044b\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0430, \u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0433\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0438 \u0421\u0412\u0422-40, \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0431\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0440-98\u041a \u0438 \u043f\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430-\u043f\u0443\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0418\u043d\u0433\u0440\u044d\u043c]</ref><ref>[https://www.kalashnikov.ru/medialibrary/1a2/pbs.pdf \u0412 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0434\u0430\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0442\u0435\u043c\u044b \u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0443\u0435\u043c \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b \u043e\u0431]</ref>\n\nAccording to certain documents (namely AVT related) and very few rare pictures, they appear to have played around with the idea of a 15-round extended magazine. No physical examples have been found however, leading to the common assumption that it was a failure (much like the AVS-36's 15-round mag). Quite a few pictures have been observed of non-Soviets (namely Germans and Finns) using SVT-38s and 40s with what appear to be [[Bren]] or [[Lahti-Saloranta M/26|LS/26]] magazines. Very little is known about usage with the unsupported magazines (including their reliability and max capacity).\n\n==SVTs outside of the Soviet Union==\nThe first country outside the Soviet Union to employ the SVT was Finland, which captured some 2,700 SVT-38s during the [[Winter War]], and over 15,000 SVTs during the [[Continuation War]]. The SVT saw extensive use in Finnish hands.<ref name=\"Finland\">{{cite book|title=Finland at War 1939\u201345|series=Elite 141|first1=Philip |last1=Jowett|first2= Brent|last2= Snodgrass|date= 5 Jul 2006|isbn=9781841769691|publisher=Osprey Publishing|page=48}}</ref> The Finns even attempted to make their own clone of the SVT-38 designated ''Tapako'', though only a prototype was ever conceived.<ref name=\"Jaeger\"/> The Finns would continue to experiment with producing their own SVT based rifles until the late 50s with the introduction of the [[RK-62]]. Germany captured hundreds of thousands of SVTs from the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]]. As the Germans were short of self-loading rifles themselves, SVT-38 and 40s, designated respectively as '''Selbstladegewehr 258(r)''' and '''Selbstladegewehr 259(r)''' by the [[Wehrmacht]], saw widespread use in German hands against their former owners. Study of the SVT's gas-operated action also aided in the development of the German [[Gewehr 43]] rifle.<ref name=\"Bishop1998\">{{cite encyclopedia|title=Tokarev rifles|encyclopedia=The encyclopedia of weapons of World War II|pages=218\u2013219|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Encyclopedia_of_Weapons_of_World_War.html?id=MuGsf0psjvcC|isbn= 9780760710227|editor-first=Chris|editor-last=Bishop|publisher=Barnes & Noble|year=1998}}</ref>\nDuring the 1940s, [[Switzerland]] began looking into equipping its military with semi-auto rifles. Although never officially adopted, [[W+F Bern]] produced an almost faithful clone of the SVT with [[7.5 mm Swiss]] chambering and a 6 round magazine called the '''AK44'''.<ref>[https://www.forgottenweapons.com/ria-prototype-wf-bern-ak44-copy-of-the-svt/ RIA: Prototype W+F Bern AK44 Copy of the SVT]</ref>\n\n==Post-war==\nAfter the war, SVTs were mostly withdrawn from service and refurbished in arsenals, then stored. In Soviet service, firearms like the [[SKS]] and the [[AK-47]] as well as the later [[Dragunov sniper rifle|SVD]] made the SVT obsolete, and the rifle was generally out of service by 1955.{{cn|date=February 2019}} Only a few SVTs were exported to Soviet allies and clients. The [[Korean People's Army]] reportedly received some before the [[Korean War]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=North Korean Small Arms (Democratic People's Republic of Korea)|magazine=Small Arms Review |volume=16|issue=2 |date=June 2012|url=https://smallarmsreview.com/display.article.cfm?idarticles=1108}}</ref><ref name=\"Korea\">{{cite book|title=Korean War Almanac|first=Paul M.|last=Edwards|isbn=0-8160-6037-1|publisher=Facts On File|chapter=Communist weapons, infantry|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816060375/page/498 498-499]|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5gYCm0bM68sC&q=SVT|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816060375/page/498|year=2006}}</ref> The Finnish Army retired the SVT in 1958, and about 7,500 rifles were sold to the United States civilian market through firearm importer [[Interarms]]. This marked the end of SVTs in regular service.\n\nIn the Soviet Union, some SVTs (without bayonets) were sold as civilian hunting rifles<ref>\u041c. \u0411\u043b\u044e\u043c, \u0410. \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043d\u043e\u0432. \u041e\u0445\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0443 \u043e \u0421\u0412\u0422 // \u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b \"\u041e\u0445\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0438 \u043e\u0445\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0447\u044c\u0435 \u0445\u043e\u0437\u044f\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\", \u2116 11, 1989</ref>, although other SVTs were kept in storage until the 1990s, when many rifles were sold abroad, along with other surplus military firearms.\n\nCurrently the SVT is fairly widely available for collectors and historical enthusiasts, and is highly sought after. In Russia, limited examples for civilian use have been sold as the \u041e\u0421\u041a-88 (OSK 88) and [[Molot]] KO-SVT with some variations in stock, barrel length and optics. The rifle's popularity is due to a combination of the inexpensive nature of its [[7.62\u00d754mmR]] ammunition, favorable [[aesthetics]], historical significance, and pleasant shooting characteristics.{{cn|date=February 2019}}\n\nDespite its relatively brief service career, the SVT was a prolific rifle on the Eastern Front during World War II, and it had considerable impact on European battle rifle designs during and immediately after the war. The German [[Gewehr 43|G-43]] was influenced by the SVT in its design, as was Simonov's experimental carbine during the closing stages of the war (which would later become the [[SKS]]). The [[FN FAL]] and its ancestor [[FN Model 1949|FN-49]] employ the same locking mechanism and operating principle as the SVT, although as mentioned above, this is most likely coincidental. As a service rifle, the SVT had its problems, but so did contemporary semi-automatic rifles made by other countries. The main reason for the gradual downfall of SVT usage in combat was not its technical disadvantages; rather, the reason was that, with the immense, continual demand for rifles in the front lines, Soviet factories could produce other, simpler designs in far greater quantities in the same length of time it took to produce the SVT. In 1944 the Soviet Union adopted the [[7.62x39]] round used in the RPD Light Machinegun, SKS, and AK-47 Rifles. In 1945 the [[SKS]] was adopted which replaced the SVT-40 as the main infantry rifle, which itself was replaced by the AK-47 in 1948.\n\n==Users==\n* {{flag|Independent State of Croatia|name=Croatia}}<ref>{{cite book|title=World War II Croation Legionaries: Croation Troops Under Axis Command 1941\u201445|author=Vladimir Brnardic|isbn=978-1-4728-1767-9|page=9|date=22 November 2016}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Czechoslovakia}}: [[1st Czechoslovak Army Corps in the USSR|1st Czechoslovak Independent Brigade in the USSR]]<ref>{{cite web|title=1st Czechoslovak Independent Brigade|url=https://www.czechpatriots.com/en/1st-czechoslovak-independent-brigade.php|website=czechpatriots.com|first=Michal|last= Gelbi\u010d|access-date=3 February 2019}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Estonia}} [[Forest Brothers|Estonian partisans]] after World War 2<ref>{{cite book|title= Germany's Eastern Front Allies (2): Baltic Forces|series=Men-at-Arms 363|last1=Nigel|first1= Thomas|first2=Carlos |last2=Caballero Jurado|date= 25 Jan 2002|isbn=9781841761930|page=40|publisher=Osprey Publishing|ref=harv}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Finland}}: Captured from Soviet troops, AVT-40 version also used.<ref name=\"Jaeger\">{{cite web|first=|last=|title=Rifles, part 4 |date=15 January 2017 |url=https://www.jaegerplatoon.net/RIFLES4.htm}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|East Germany}} [[East Germany|German Democratic Republic]] after WWII, issued as the '''SWT'''<ref>[https://www.tankograd.com/cms/website.php?id=/en/Fahrzeuge-und-Waffen-der-Nationalen-Volksarmee-3.htm Military and Paramilitary Vehicles and Weapons of East Germany]</ref>\n* {{flag|Georgia}}<ref name ='SAS 1998 4'>{{cite book|url=http://www.smallarmssurvey.org/fileadmin/docs/B-Occasional-papers/SAS-OP06-Georgia.pdf|chapter-url=|chapter=|title=Politics From The Barrel of a Gun|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=1998|author=Small Arms Survey|pages=40|isbn=|author-link=Small Arms Survey}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Lithuania}}: Lithuanian civil Police used captured SVT-40s during the [[German occupation of Lithuania during World War II|German occupation]].{{sfn|Nigel|Caballero Jurado|2002|p=46}}\n* {{flag|Nazi Germany}} (Captured from Soviet troops)<ref>{{cite book|title=Desperate Measures: The Last-Ditch Weapons of the Nazi Volkssturm|page=61|author=W. Darrin Weaver|year=2005|publisher=Collector Grade Publications|isbn=0889353727}}</ref>\n* {{flag|North Korea}}\n* {{flagicon|Hungary}} [[People's Republic of Hungary]]{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n* {{flag|Poland}}: [[Polish Armed Forces in the East]]<ref name=\"mcnab2002\">{{cite book |last=McNab |first=Chris|title=20th Century Military Uniforms |year=2002 |edition=2nd |publisher=Grange Books |location=Kent |isbn=1-84013-476-3|page=191}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Romania}} [[Socialist Republic of Romania|People's Republic of Romania]]{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n* {{flag|Soviet Union}}\n* {{flag|Switzerland}} (AK-44 clone)\n* {{flag|Ukraine}}: 11,500 stored in 2008<ref>{{cite web|lang=uk|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0434\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0443 \u0432\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u0430\u0439\u043d\u0430 \u0417\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b, \u044f\u043a\u0435 \u043c\u043e\u0436\u0435 \u0431\u0443\u0442\u0438 \u0432\u0456\u0434\u0447\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043e|url=https://zakon4.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/1092-2008-%D1%80|website=zakon4.rada.gov.ua|date=6 August 2008|trans-title=On Approval of the List of Military Property of the Armed Forces, which may be alienated}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Vietnam}}: limited service.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Chien Cu-War Material|page=9|author=Nguyen-Khanh Maj. Gen. & Tran-Van-Minh Maj. Gen.|year=1964}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Chicom Series|page=106|author=Granville N Rideout|year=1971|edition=1st|publisher=Yankee Pub. Co}}</ref><ref>[https://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2014/11/17/strange-guns-viet-cong-svt-40/ Strange Guns: Viet-Cong SVT-40]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[AVS-36]]\n* [[FG 42]]\n* [[Gewehr 43]]\n* [[M1 Garand]]\n* [[M1941 Johnson rifle]]\n* [[SKS]]\n* [[List of Russian weaponry]]\n* [[Lyudmila Pavlichenko]]\n\n== Museum exhibits ==\n* One SVT-38 rifle, one SVT-40 rifle and one SKT-40 carbine are in collection of Tula State Arms Museum in [[Tula Kremlin]]<ref>\"''\u041a\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0439 \u0424. \u0412. \u0422\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u044b\u043c \u043e\u043f\u044b\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0446\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0438\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0445 \u0441 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u0448\u0442\u0430\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043a \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0446\u0430 1938 \u0433. \u0438 1940 \u0433. \u0432 \u043a\u043e\u043b\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0435\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0435, \u0438\u043c\u0435\u044e\u0449\u0435\u0435 \u043c\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435. ... \u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0431\u0438\u043d \u0422\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430 \u0421\u041a\u0422-40, \u0440\u0435\u0434\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044f\u0448\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u0435\u043d\u044c \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0446, \u0431\u044b\u043b \u043b\u0438\u0447\u043d\u044b\u043c \u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0435\u043c \u0412. \u0413. \u0416\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430, \u0441\u0435\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0440\u044f \u0422\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0412\u041a\u041f (\u0431), \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0422\u0443\u043b\u044b \u043e\u0441\u0435\u043d\u044c\u044e 1941 \u0433.''\"<br />[http://www.museum-arms.ru/collections/automat-battlearms/ \u041e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0435 \u0431\u043e\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0435 \u0430\u0432\u0442\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435] / \u043e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u0422\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u044f \u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u044f</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|SVT-40}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20031216033834/http://world.guns.ru/rifle/rfl06-e.htm History and technicalities of the SVT-40]\n* [http://www.mosinnagant.net/USSR/SVTsection.asp SVT info and pictures at Mosin-Nagant.net, compiled by Vic Thomas]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091113091311/http://50ae.net/collection/svt40/ SVT-40 Pictorial]\n* [http://www.kalashnikov.ru/upload/medialibrary/3fb/50_56.pdf \u0421\u0412\u0422 \u0442\u0440\u0443\u0434\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u0443\u0434\u044c\u0431\u0430], Kalashnikov magazine, 2001/6, pp.&nbsp;50\u201356\n* [https://forums.gunboards.com/showthread.php?504617-Tokarev-SVT-40-Identifying-collecting-and-FAQ Tokarev SVT-40. Identifying, collecting and FAQ]\n\n{{WWIIUSSRInfWeapons}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:7.62\u00d754mmR battle rifles]] <!-- AVT-40 variant -->\n[[Category:7.62\u00d754mmR semi-automatic rifles]]\n[[Category:Short stroke piston firearms]]\n[[Category:Tula Arms Plant products]]\n[[Category:Semi-automatic rifles of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:World War II battle rifles]]\n[[Category:World War II semi-automatic rifles]]\n[[Category:World War II infantry weapons of the Soviet Union]]\n", "name_user": "Abcspaghetti", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVT-40"}
{"title_page": "Chris Chike", "text_new": "'''Chris Chike''' (User names in YouTube: '''iamchris4life''' and '''CHRS4LFE'''. Dance Dance Revolution [DDR] player ID: '''CHRS4LFE'''.) is known for his skill in a variety of [[music video game]]s.\n\n== Notable accomplishments ==\n\n===''Guitar Hero''===\n\nChris holds the official Guinness world record for \"Highest score for a single song on ''[[Guitar Hero III: Legends of Rock]]''\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Guinness Book of World Records: Gamers Edition}}</ref> On March 11, 2008, he managed to achieve 97 percent completion rate and 840,647 points in [[DragonForce]]'s \"[[Through the Fire and Flames]]\" in front of Guinness judges. His current record, not confirmed by Guinness is 99 percent completion with 975,412 points.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/10/arts/television/10itzk.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Chris Chike Is Guitar Hero's Hero |first=David|last=Itzkov|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 10, 2008}}</ref>\n\nChris was crowned the Guitar Hero III champion at the National [[Play N Trade]] tournament in [[Bloomington, Minnesota|Bloomington]], [[Minnesota]]. Local tournaments were held March 15 and 16, with close to 1,000 gamers at more than 100 Play N Trade video game stores across the country competing.<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2008_March_19/ai_n24928493 Chris Chike, World Record Holder], Bnet.com, March 19, 2008</ref> He won $2,000 from his first-place performance in the song, \"Through the Fire and Flames\".\n\n===''Dance Dance Revolution''===\nChris took 1st place in [[Dance Dance Revolution]] at the 6th Annual Konami Arcade Championship Finals on February 11, 2017, taking place at the [[Japan Amusement Expo]] 2017.<ref>[http://p.eagate.573.jp/game/kac6th/detail.html?id=ddr&group=final&tab=result&lang=en#_tablevel2 Chris Chike, DDRA Champion], February 11, 2017</ref> This was the first year that players from North America were allowed to participate.\n\nChris automatically qualified for the 7th Annual Konami Arcade Championship,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=David |title=The 7th KAC Preliminaries Results \u2013 DDRCommunity |url=http://ddrcommunity.com/the-7th-kac-preliminaries-results/ |website=DDRCommunity |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> which took place on February 10, 2018, due to winning the championship the year prior. He ultimately finished as the runner-up to Korean DDR player Yoon Sang Yeon (DDR player ID: '''FEFEMZ''').\n\nChris was seeded #1 in the world for the 8th Konami Arcade Championship, held in January 2019. However, he was again the runner-up, as '''FEFEMZ''' repeated his first-place finish.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=David |title=The 8th KONAMI Arcade Championship Results \u2013 DDRCommunity |url=http://ddrcommunity.com/the-8th-konami-arcade-championship-results/ |website=DDRCommunity |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nChris was seeded #1 in the world for the 9th Konami Arcade Championship, held in February 2020. He finished first place.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=David |title=The 9th KONAMI Arcade Championship Final Results \u2013 DDRCommunity |url=http://ddrcommunity.com/the-9th-konami-arcade-championship-final-results/ |website=DDRCommunity |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chike, Chris}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:American esports players]]\n[[Category:Guitar Hero players]]\n[[Category:People from Rochester, Minnesota]]\n\n\n{{eSports-player-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Chris Chike''' (User names in YouTube: '''iamchris4life''' and '''CHRS4LFE'''. Dance Dance Revolution [DDR] player ID: '''CHRS4LFE'''.) is known for his skill in a variety of [[music video game]]s.\n\n== Notable accomplishments ==\n\n===''Guitar Hero''===\n\nChris holds the official Guinness world record for \"Highest score for a single song on ''[[Guitar Hero III: Legends of Rock]]''\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Guinness Book of World Records: Gamers Edition}}</ref> On March 11, 2008, he managed to achieve 97 percent completion rate and 840,647 points in [[DragonForce]]'s \"[[Through the Fire and Flames]]\" in front of Guinness judges. His current record, not confirmed by Guinness is 99 percent completion with 975,412 points.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/10/arts/television/10itzk.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Chris Chike Is Guitar Hero's Hero |first=David|last=Itzkov|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 10, 2008}}</ref>\n\nChris was crowned the Guitar Hero III champion at the National [[Play N Trade]] tournament in [[Bloomington, Minnesota|Bloomington]], [[Minnesota]]. Local tournaments were held March 15 and 16, with close to 1,000 gamers at more than 100 Play N Trade video game stores across the country competing.<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2008_March_19/ai_n24928493 Chris Chike, World Record Holder], Bnet.com, March 19, 2008</ref> He won $2,000 from his first-place performance in the song, \"Through the Fire and Flames\".\n\n===''Dance Dance Revolution''===\nChris took 1st place in [[Dance Dance Revolution]] at the 6th Annual Konami Arcade Championship Finals on February 11, 2017, taking place at the [[Japan Amusement Expo]] 2017.<ref>[http://p.eagate.573.jp/game/kac6th/detail.html?id=ddr&group=final&tab=result&lang=en#_tablevel2 Chris Chike, DDRA Champion], February 11, 2017</ref> This was the first year that players from North America were allowed to participate.\n\nChris automatically qualified for the 7th Annual Konami Arcade Championship,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=David |title=The 7th KAC Preliminaries Results \u2013 DDRCommunity |url=http://ddrcommunity.com/the-7th-kac-preliminaries-results/ |website=DDRCommunity |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> which took place on February 10, 2018, due to winning the championship the year prior. He ultimately finished as the runner-up to Korean DDR player Yoon Sang Yeon (DDR player ID: '''FEFEMZ''').\n\nChris was seeded #1 in the world for the 8th Konami Arcade Championship, held in January 2019. However, he was again the runner-up, as '''FEFEMZ''' repeated his first place finish.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=David |title=The 8th KONAMI Arcade Championship Results \u2013 DDRCommunity |url=http://ddrcommunity.com/the-8th-konami-arcade-championship-results/ |website=DDRCommunity |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nChris was seeded #1 in the world for the 9th Konami Arcade Championship, held in February 2020. He finished first place.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=David |title=The 9th KONAMI Arcade Championship Final Results \u2013 DDRCommunity |url=http://ddrcommunity.com/the-9th-konami-arcade-championship-final-results/ |website=DDRCommunity |accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chike, Chris}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:American esports players]]\n[[Category:Guitar Hero players]]\n[[Category:People from Rochester, Minnesota]]\n\n\n{{eSports-player-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nealbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e''Dance Dance Revolution'':clean up,typo(s) fixed: first place \u2192 first-place", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Chike"}
{"title_page": "United Football League (2009\u20132012)", "text_new": "{{short description|Defunct American professional football league}}\n{{Infobox sports league\n| title          = United Football League\n| logo           = United Football League (2009) logo.png\n| pixels         = 200px\n| current_season = \n| last_season    = 2012 UFL season\n| sport          = [[American football]]\n| founded        = 2007\n| inaugural      = 2009\n| folded         = 2012\n| slogan         = {{nobr|\"If you like great football, you will love the UFL\"}}\n| teams          = 4\n| country        = United States\n| champion       = [[Virginia Destroyers]] (1st)\n| most_champs    = [[Las Vegas Locomotives]] (2)\n| ceo            = [[Bill Hambrecht]] (majority owner)\n| TV             = [[CBS Sports Network]] (2012)<br>[[Comcast SportsNet]] (2011)<br>[[AXS TV|HDNet]], [[Versus (TV channel)|Versus]] (2009\u201310)\n|notes=\n}}\n\nThe '''United Football League''' ('''UFL''') was a [[professional football (gridiron)|professional]] [[American football]] league based in the United States that [[2009 UFL season|began play in October 2009]] and played four seasons, [[2012 UFL season|the most recent being cut short in October 2012]]. The small league, which never had more than five teams playing at one time, played most of its games in markets where the [[National Football League]] (NFL) had no current presence.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSN1529711620080515 |title=NFL rival to reveal West Coast football teams soon |first=Ben |last=Klayman |date=2008-05-15 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=2009-02-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211124304/http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSN1529711620080515 |archivedate=2008-12-11 }}</ref> Unlike most alternative professional football leagues since the 1980s, the UFL played all of its games in the traditional fall season, competing directly with the NFL, [[college football]], and [[high school football]].\n\nThe UFL occupied the second tier of professional football in the United States, behind the National Football League.<ref>[http://www.masslive.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/07/hartford_colonials_could_fold.html Hartford Colonials could fold as part of UFL contraction] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925033338/http://www.masslive.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/07/hartford_colonials_could_fold.html |date=2012-09-25 }}. Associated Press. Retrieved July 27, 2011.</ref><ref name=wavy72612>[https://archive.is/20130209031652/http://www.wavy.com/dpp/sports/destroyers-and-ufl-back-for-another-go Destroyers and UFL back for another go]. ''WAVY-TV''. Retrieved July 26, 2012.</ref> The UFL primarily consisted of players who had previously played for an NFL team. Although the league had no connection with the NFL, and had never intended to foster any such connection,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fanhouse.com/2009/10/03/ex-ny-giants-coach-fassel-ufl-has-staying-power/|title=Ex-NY Giants Coach Fassel: UFL Has Staying Power|work=[[FanHouse]]|first=Anthony|last=Olivieri|date=2009-10-03|accessdate=2009-10-05}}</ref> some speculated that it could have become a minor or \"developmental\" league for the NFL,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/story/11569904|title=NFL could find new UFL to be a nice development|last=Prisco|first=Pete|date=2009-03-30|work=[[CBS Sports]]|accessdate=2009-04-01|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016051257/http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/story/11569904|archivedate=2012-10-16}}</ref> including the UFL's own commissioner.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/football/2009-10-15-sw-united-football-league_N.htm | work=USA Today | first=Sean | last=Leahy | title=Will the UFL be able to find a niche as NFL's minor league? | date=2009-10-15}}</ref>\n\nEarly news reports had speculated that based on the UFL's initial plan the league would become a \"competitor\" to the NFL.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/30/business/global/30spot.html?_r=3&ref=global|title=A Disruptive Venture Capitalist Shakes Up a New Field|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Holly Hubbard|last=Preston|date=2009-05-29|accessdate=2009-11-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170429002006/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/30/business/global/30spot.html?_r=3&ref=global|archivedate=2017-04-29}}</ref> The UFL seemed poised to capitalize on fan disgust with the NFL should the established league lock out its players prior to the 2011\u221212 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=garber_greg&id=6182314|title=Garber: Would lockout open door for UFL?|date=7 March 2011|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=29 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520070831/http://www.espn.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=garber_greg&id=6182314|archivedate=20 May 2017}}</ref> The thought was that the NFL would fail to reach an agreement with the [[National Football League Players Association|NFL players' union]] after the end of their collective bargaining agreement. This would have led to the 2011\u221212 NFL season being delayed or cancelled, leaving the UFL the only pro football available.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadspin.com/5797726/ufl-to-conduct-player-draft-on-twitter-tonight|title=UFL To Conduct Player Draft On Twitter Tonight|first=Barry|last=Petchesky|website=deadspin.com|accessdate=29 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520045822/http://deadspin.com/5797726/ufl-to-conduct-player-draft-on-twitter-tonight|archivedate=20 May 2017}}</ref>  The NFL did lock out their players, but the situation was resolved in July 2011, before the start of the NFL season.  This negated any benefits the UFL might have hoped to reap from the labor dispute.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=clayton_john&id=3972890|title=NFL labor strife would help UFL's cause|last=Clayton|first=John|date=2009-03-12|work=NFL|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=2009-03-13|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090314000122/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=clayton_john&id=3972890|archivedate=2009-03-14}}</ref>\n\nThe league was beset by frequent operational interruptions, stemming from systemic financial shortfalls, especially from summer 2011 onward. The United Football League announced on October 20, 2012, that it was ceasing operations immediately, after four weeks of play. The official line from the league was that they intended to resume operations and complete the unfinished 2012 schedule at an unspecified time in spring 2013, then revert to a fall schedule in fall 2013 without a full off-season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.omahanighthawks.com/2012/10/20/ufl-suspends-operations-for-2012-season/|title=UFL suspends operations for 2012 season|work=Omaha Nighthawks|publisher=Omaha Nighthawks|date=2012-10-20|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024013843/http://www.omahanighthawks.com/2012/10/20/ufl-suspends-operations-for-2012-season/|archivedate=2012-10-24}}</ref> This announcement, however, was met with widespread skepticism from both within and outside the league, skepticism that was proven to be warranted as the league never returned.<ref name=carp1021>Carp, Steve (October 21, 2012). [http://www.lvrj.com/sports/united-football-league-suspends-operations-175080681.html United Football League suspends operations]. ''Las Vegas Review-Journal''. Retrieved October 21, 2012.</ref><ref>Smith, Michael David (October 20, 2012). [http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2012/10/20/ufl-calls-off-its-season/ UFL calls off its season] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022224255/http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2012/10/20/ufl-calls-off-its-season/ |date=2012-10-22 }}. ''ProFootballTalk.com''. Retrieved October 22, 2012.</ref><ref>Robinson, Tom (October 24, 2012). [http://hamptonroads.com/2012/10/destroyers-coach-unsure-league-can-continue Destroyers coach unsure league can continue] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028171258/http://hamptonroads.com/2012/10/destroyers-coach-unsure-league-can-continue |date=2012-10-28 }}. ''The Virginian-Pilot''. Retrieved October 25, 2012.</ref>\n\nOver the course of the league's history, the [[Las Vegas Locomotives]] were the most successful team, winning two of the three [[UFL Championship Game|championships]], appearing in (but losing) the third, and having a perfect record for the season at the time of the cessation of operations.\n\n==History==\n===Development and first season (2007\u20132009)===\n{{see also|2009 UFL season}}\n[[File:uflleague08.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Original UFL logo (2007\u20132008)]]\nThe United Football League was founded by [[Bill Hambrecht]] and [[Tim Armstrong (executive)|Tim Armstrong]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ufl-football.com/about-us|title=About us|publisher=UFL Football|accessdate=3 February 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201233503/http://www.ufl-football.com/about-us|archivedate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\nThe UFL initially had plans to start with eight teams with $12\u201320 million rosters playing in targeted sites in the fall of 2008.{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}} [[T. Boone Pickens]] and [[Mark Cuban]] had originally been in discussion with the league as potential owners,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/03/sports/playmagazine/0603play-business.html?em&ex=1180670400&en=b61c332c7e9d78ad&ei=5070&_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Joe | last=Nocera | title=First and Long &mdash; Very Long | date=2007-06-03 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206074517/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/03/sports/playmagazine/0603play-business.html?em&ex=1180670400&en=b61c332c7e9d78ad&ei=5070&_r=0 | archivedate=2017-12-06 }}</ref> but both backed out prior to the 2009 season. On February 9, 2009, it was announced that [[Paul Pelosi]], husband of [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] [[Nancy Pelosi]], was one of four investors who had stepped forward to invest $10,000,000, plus a personal commitment to cover opening-season losses up to another $10,000,000 for a one-half interest in four franchises to play in the league's 2009 inaugural season. The league was under the overall direction of William Hambrecht, a former [[Wall Street]] figure who had sold his old firm, Hambrecht & Quist, to what was then [[JPMorgan Chase|Chase Manhattan Bank]] for US$1.35 billion in 1999.<ref>{{cite news|title=Football's new game in town|url=http://finance.fortune.cnn.com/2010/10/08/footballs-new-game-in-town/|accessdate=September 4, 2012|work=CNN|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511142421/http://finance.fortune.cnn.com/2010/10/08/footballs-new-game-in-town/|archivedate=May 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Michael Huyghue]], a former executive with the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] and the head of a sports agency service, was the league's first and only commissioner.\n\nThe league had identified 21 cities that they deemed possessed strong economic bases, passionate football tradition, and a high number of average TV viewing households as potential team locations. Target markets in the US included: [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]], [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], [[Las Vegas]], Los Angeles, [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Milwaukee]], New York City, [[Oklahoma City]], [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Raleigh-Durham]], [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[Salt Lake City]], [[San Antonio]], and [[San Jose, California|San Jose]]; as well as international markets in London, Mexico City and [[Monterrey, Mexico|Monterrey]].<ref>{{cite news|title=About the United Football League (UFL)|url=http://www.ufl2008.com/about_the_ufl.html|publisher=ufl2008.com|date=September 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071218192743/http://www.ufl2008.com/about_the_ufl.html|archivedate=December 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\nWith their planned launch date arriving soon and only a couple owners in hand, the UFL decided to go ahead and do a \"soft launch\" in 2009, similar to the one used by the [[Arena Football League]] in its [[1987 Arena Football League season|inaugural season]] in 1987,<ref>{{cite news|url= http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/peter_king/10/11/weeks/.html|title= Broncos, Bengals open some eyes with impressive week 5 wins|work = [[Sports Illustrated]]|first= Peter |last= King|date= 2009-10-12|accessdate= 2012-09-02}}</ref> rather than delaying play another year. The soft launch called for opening the league with fewer teams than planned and playing an abbreviated schedule. They hoped a functioning league would yield the UFL a superior position for attracting potential owners over competing leagues still under development (like the New USFL, which at the time was trumpeting a spring 2010 launch).\n\nThe markets chosen for the [[2009 UFL season|premiere season]] were New York City ([[Hartford Colonials|Sentinels]]), Las Vegas ([[Las Vegas Locomotives|Locomotives]]), Orlando ([[Florida Tuskers]]), and the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] ([[Sacramento Mountain Lions|California Redwoods]]).  The league's short schedule made the kind of expensive promotional efforts often employed with a new league cost prohibitive. Additionally, the league had a full schedule of three home games in the same stadium in only one of their selected cities, Las Vegas.\n\nDuring the week of August 10, 2009, the four team names and their uniform jerseys were revealed. Each of the uniforms (and the team logos and helmets that were unveiled on October 2)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/United-Football-League-prnews-3774862174.html?x=0&.v=1|title=United Football League Reveals Team Logos for 'Premiere' Season|work=[[Yahoo! Finance]]|date=2009-10-02|accessdate=2009-11-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091009203736/http://finance.yahoo.com/news/United-Football-League-prnews-3774862174.html?x=0&.v=1|archive-date=2009-10-09|url-status=dead}}</ref> incorporated the UFL's signature color scheme into their designs, including silver (primary color for the Las Vegas Locomotives), blue ([[Florida Tuskers]]), black (New York Sentinels), and lime green and white (California Redwoods). Each of the team jerseys had the same design template, complete with a horizontal arc across the top front that resembles the arc on the UFL's logo.\n\nOne of the Redwoods' games was moved to San Jose; the other two were played in San Francisco (the move to San Jose was a short-notice move due to poor attendance in San Francisco; however, the San Jose game ended up being even more poorly attended). The league was unable to secure a fiscally reasonable deal for a stadium within New York City, forcing the league to have the Sentinels play one home game each in [[Hartford, Connecticut]]; on the campus of [[Hofstra University]] in [[Long Island]], and in [[New Jersey]]. In addition, one of the Tuskers' games was played at [[Tropicana Field]] in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]], in part because the Tuskers shared ownership that year with the [[Tampa Bay Rays]]; this was not reprised in 2010.\n\nThe Florida Tuskers finished 2009 with a 6&ndash;0 record. The Las Vegas Locomotives were next at 4&ndash;2, the California Redwoods were 2&ndash;4, and the Sentinels were last at 0&ndash;6. The Locomotives played the Tuskers in the [[2009 UFL Championship Game]]; the Locomotives won the title on a field goal in overtime.\n\n===Expansion (2010)===\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ United Football League Progression\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Teams\n! scope=\"col\"| Games Played\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[2009 UFL season|2009]]\n| 4\n| 6\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[2010 UFL season|2010]]\n| 5\n| 8\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[2011 UFL season|2011]]\n| 4\n| 4\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[2012 UFL season|2012]]\n| 4\n| 4\n|}\n\n{{see also|2010 UFL season}}\nBefore the 2010 season, the New York Sentinels permanently settled in [[Hartford, Connecticut]], becoming the [[Hartford Colonials]]. The new name was chosen by fans through an online vote.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.courant.com/sports/football/hc-ufl-hartford-team-name314.artmar14,0,4606213.story |title= Hartford UFL Team Now Has A Name |date= March 14, 2010 |newspaper= [[The Hartford Courant]] |accessdate=March 14, 2010}}</ref> The California Redwoods relocated to [[Sacramento, California]], and chose the name Mountain Lions, also from a fan vote. In another change for the 2010 season, each UFL team would gain their own uniform color identity, loosening them from the standard league colors.\n\nFor 2010, the league indicated that five markets were under consideration for expansion teams: [[Omaha, Nebraska]]; [[San Antonio]] or [[Austin, Texas]]; [[Portland, Oregon]]; and [[Salt Lake City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lvrj.com/sports/locos-remain-part-of-leagues-future-74533382.html|title=UFL: Locos remain part of league's future|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|first=Steve|last=Carp|date=2009-11-26|accessdate=2010-05-20|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091129094433/http://www.lvrj.com/sports/locos-remain-part-of-leagues-future-74533382.html|archivedate=2009-11-29}}</ref> On April 15, 2010, Omaha was granted an expansion team, called the [[Omaha Nighthawks]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.omaha.com/article/20100331/NEWS01/703319896 |title=New sport for new stadium? |first=Jeffrey |last=Robb |date=2010-03-31 |publisher=[[Omaha World Herald]] |accessdate=2010-03-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120905180924/http://www.omaha.com/article/20100331/NEWS01/703319896 |archivedate=2012-09-05 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.omaha.com/article/20100413/NEWS01/100419825#ufl-plans-announcement |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100416171015/http://omaha.com/article/20100413/NEWS01/100419825#ufl-plans-announcement |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-04-16 |title=UFL plans announcement |first=Thad |last=Livingston |date=2010-04-13 |publisher=[[Omaha World Herald]] |accessdate=2010-04-13 }}</ref>\n\n[[Mark Cuban]], who was mentioned as a potential franchise owner in the league's formative stages, loaned the league $5 million in April 2010. He did not own a franchise and he was not involved in day-to-day operations of the league nor of any of its teams.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/dallas/nba/news/story?id=5131063 Cuban is newest league owner in UFL] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120190705/http://sports.espn.go.com/dallas/nba/news/story?id=5131063 |date=2016-01-20 }}. [[KESN]]. Retrieved 2010-04-24.</ref> In January 2011, Cuban, the owner of the [[Dallas Mavericks]] and majority owner of HDNet (now [[AXS TV]]), a cable channel and Web-streaming service which had broadcast some games of the league's inaugural two seasons, filed a federal lawsuit against the UFL for their failure to repay the loan by the October 6, 2010, deadline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.dallasobserver.com/unfairpark/2011/01/mark_cuban_files_federal_suit.php|title=Mark Cuban Files Federal Suit to Get Back His $5 Million Loan to the United Football League|work=[[Dallas Observer]] |first=Robert |last=Wilonsky |date=2011-01-13 |accessdate=2011-01-13|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20110608004326/http://blogs.dallasobserver.com/unfairpark/2011/01/mark_cuban_files_federal_suit.php|archivedate=2011-06-08}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2011 season, the UFL announced the addition of [[UFL Virginia|a franchise]] in the [[Hampton Roads]] ([[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk]] metro area) region of [[Virginia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wavy.com/dpp/sports/beach-courts-ufl-team|title=Beach Courts UFL Team|work=[[WAVY-TV]] |first=Bruce |last=Rader |date=2010-06-30 |accessdate=2010-08-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928020216/http://www.wavy.com/dpp/sports/beach-courts-ufl-team|archivedate=2011-09-28}}</ref> originally owned by former [[Canadian Football League|CFL]] owner [[Jim Speros]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/more/06/21/ufl.norfolk.ap/ |title=UFL to add Virginia team for 2011 season |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=2010-06-21 |accessdate=2010-06-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20100626022608/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/more/06/21/ufl.norfolk.ap/ |archivedate=June 26, 2010}}</ref> and managed by former NFL and [[United States Football League|USFL]] quarterback [[Doug Williams (American football)|Doug Williams]]. Soon after Speros' ownership was announced, he relinquished control of the team to the league and allowed bidding to be opened again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ufl-football.com/news/statement-ufl-virginia |title=Statement on UFL Virginia |work=United Football League |date=2010-08-20 |accessdate=2010-08-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717140616/http://www.ufl-football.com/news/statement-ufl-virginia |archivedate=July 17, 2011 }}</ref> Williams later joined his alma mater [[Grambling State Tigers|Grambling State University]] as their head coach, resigning as Destroyers' general manager.\n\nThe UFL announced former [[TD Ameritrade]] [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]] [[Joe Moglia]] as the first head coach and president of the Destroyers in November 2010;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fanhouse.com/2010/11/10/joe-moglia-officially-named-virginia-destroyers-head-coach-pres/|title=Joe Moglia Officially Named Virginia Destroyers Head Coach, President|work=[[FanHouse]]|first=Robert|last=Karpeles|date=2011-01-12|accessdate=2011-01-12}}</ref> however, in January 2011, the league announced Moglia would instead coach the Omaha Nighthawks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fanhouse.com/2011/01/12/joe-moglia-to-coach-omaha-nighthawks/|title=Joe Moglia to Coach Omaha Nighthawks|work=[[FanHouse]]|first=Robert|last=Karpeles|date=2011-01-12|accessdate=2011-01-12}}</ref> At the same time, the Florida Tuskers ceased operations in Orlando and moved to Virginia, with Jay Gruden initially remaining as the Destroyers' coach; however, Gruden was hired the next month by the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] of the NFL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ufl-football.com/news/jay-gruden-coach-virginia-destroyers-united-football-league|title=Jay Gruden to Coach the Virginia Destroyers of the United Football League|work=United Football League|date=2011-01-12|accessdate=2011-01-12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110116044048/http://www.ufl-football.com/news/jay-gruden-coach-virginia-destroyers-united-football-league|archivedate=2011-01-16}}</ref>\n\nFor possible 2011 expansion, all cities that were in consideration for 2010 (Portland, San Antonio, Austin, and Salt Lake City) remained in consideration, as well as [[Raleigh, North Carolina]]; Los Angeles; and Honolulu.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twitter.com/UFLCommissioner/status/17011761030|title=We just added our sixth city \u2013 Norfolk. Now we're considering Portland, Raleigh, St. Lake City, San Antonio, Austin, Los Angeles and Hawaii|work=Twitter|first=Michael|last=Huyghue|date=2010-06-25|accessdate=2010-06-25}}</ref> In regards to future expansion, Huyghue has said that they \"may never have more than eight teams\" depending on the league's economic situation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/peter_king/10/11/week5/1.html|title=Broncos, Bengals open some eyes with impressive Week 5 wins|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|first=Peter|last=King|date=2009-10-12|accessdate=2009-11-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015091923/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/peter_king/10/11/week5/1.html|archivedate=2009-10-15}}</ref>\n\nThe league announced it would expand into the [[Hampton Roads]] region of [[Virginia]] prior to the start of the 2011 season, giving the [[Virginia Destroyers]] time to organize. During UFL Championship Week 2010, the league announced it had a seventh franchise in place, with Huyghue indicating that it would most likely be in Los Angeles, and that the team would not be officially announced until an eighth franchise was confirmed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sacbee.com/2010/11/27/3214185/ufl-chief-pleased-by-league-growth.html |title=UFL chief pleased by league growth, Mountain Lions |work=[[The Sacramento Bee]] |first=Dave |last=Carpenter |date=2010-11-27 |accessdate=2011-01-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201235343/http://www.sacbee.com/2010/11/27/3214185/ufl-chief-pleased-by-league-growth.html |archivedate=2010-12-01 }}</ref> As events would turn out, neither franchise would materialize.\n\n===Contraction (2011)===\n{{see also|2011 UFL season}}\nThe league suffered a setback when they had to fold the [[Florida Tuskers]] in January 2011. The league moved most of the Tuskers' staff to the Destroyers and reassigned the coaching staff already in Virginia to Omaha, firing the previous Omaha coaching staff. After this, the league reduced their goal to six teams, with [[Portland, Oregon]], Salt Lake City and new contender [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], still in consideration, and Los Angeles no longer in consideration for the third consecutive year. If a sixth team had been added, the schedule for each team would have expanded to ten games.<ref>{{cite web|last=Carp|first=Steve|url=http://www.lvrj.com/sports/ufl-also-in-crisis-mode-120440374.html?ref=374|title=UFL also in crisis mode|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=April 22, 2011|accessdate=April 24, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010202254/http://www.lvrj.com/sports/ufl-also-in-crisis-mode-120440374.html?ref=374|archivedate=October 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe schedule for the [[2011 UFL season]], released June 9, 2011, confirmed that the league would be locked at five teams for the season, with no expansion. The 2011 season was to shift from a traditional late fall schedule to a late summer/early fall schedule beginning in August 2011 and ending in October; however, in July 2011, the UFL announced it would delay the start of its season until mid-September due to financial issues. The league was in negotiations with CBS and TNT for coverage after Versus dropped the UFL as part of its rebranding to [[NBCSN|NBC Sports Network]], but was unable to get any, and the league also lost its existing television partners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/#!/nfl/story/15333760/financial-problems-force-ufl-to-delay-start-of-season|title=Financial problems force UFL to delay start of season|work=CBSSports.com|date=July 19, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010005500/http://www.cbssports.com/#!/nfl/story/15333760/financial-problems-force-ufl-to-delay-start-of-season|archivedate=October 10, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ufl-football.com/news/letter-commissioner-huyghue|title=Letter from Commissioner Huyghue|publisher=United Football League|date=July 19, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724132747/http://www.ufl-football.com/news/letter-commissioner-huyghue|archivedate=July 24, 2011}}</ref> After this postponement, the league confirmed it was considering even further contraction, with the [[Hartford Colonials]] potentially on the chopping block.<ref>[http://www.courant.com/sports/football/hc-hartford-colonials-ufl-fold-20110727,0,916388.story Despite Rumors, UFL, Jerry Glanville Say Hartford Colonials Still Alive ... For Now]. ''Hartford Courant''. Retrieved July 27, 2011.</ref> On August 10, 2011, the UFL announced that it would \"suspend operations\" of the Colonials and go forward with a four-team league.<ref>[http://www.ufl-football.com/news/omaha-and-sacramento-host-opening-games-four-team-2011-united-football-league-season-september Omaha And Sacramento To Host Opening Games Of Four-Team 2011 United Football League Season In September] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912090347/http://www.ufl-football.com/news/omaha-and-sacramento-host-opening-games-four-team-2011-united-football-league-season-september |date=September 12, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n[[Jerry Glanville]], a UFL consultant who had previously been announced as the new head coach of the now-suspended Colonials, began a listening tour of Chattanooga, Salt Lake City and [[Jackson, Mississippi]], in October 2011 to gauge support for UFL expansion franchises. He has stated that of the three, at least \"one has a UFL team and one may get a UFL team.\"<ref>Glanville, Jerry (October 3, 2011).[https://www.twitter.com/JerryGlanville/status/120851369304395777 Travel this week\u2026 One has a #UFL team and one may get a #UFL team. Stay tuned.] Retrieved October 4, 2011.</ref>\n\nOn October 16, 2011, immediately after each team's fourth game, numerous reports indicated that the remainder of the 2011 season had been cancelled and that the [[2011 UFL Championship Game]] between Las Vegas and Virginia would be moved up to the date of Virginia's last home game, which would have taken place against Omaha on October 21.<ref>Florio, Mike (October 16, 2011). [http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/10/16/ufl-fast-forwarding-to-title-gam/ UFL fast forwarding to title game, extinction] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017135807/http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/10/16/ufl-fast-forwarding-to-title-gam/ |date=2011-10-17 }}. ''Pro Football Talk''. Retrieved October 16, 2011.</ref> This is in fact what happened; in addition to the championship game between Virginia and Las Vegas, the season concluded with a third-place game (on the same day) in Omaha between the other two teams, the first such game in outdoor professional gridiron football since the demise of the NFL's old third-place game, the [[Playoff Bowl]], which was last contested in January 1970 following the [[1969 National Football League season|1969 season]].\n\n===2012===\n{{main|2012 UFL season}}\nDespite the difficulties of 2011, UFL officials were on record as wanting to move ahead on future plans for the league. An April 2012 ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]'' report indicated that the UFL would announce plans on May 1 to field a five-team league for the 2012 season, including the four 2011 teams plus a fifth expansion team. (The ''Review-Journal'' report mentioned [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], [[Southern California]], and [[Portland, Oregon]] were expansion candidates.) The report also indicated that the UFL was arranging a broadcast TV deal with [[CBS Sports Network]] (a deal the league had desperately sought) to go along with regional supplemental coverage.<ref name=LVRJ-04072012>[http://www.lvrj.com/sports/ufl-not-done-yet-league-set-to-return-146516555.html \"UFL not done yet; league set to return,\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120409004429/http://www.lvrj.com/sports/ufl-not-done-yet-league-set-to-return-146516555.html |date=2012-04-09 }} from ''Las Vegas Review-Journal'', 4/7/2012</ref> However, May 1 came and went without any official announcement by the UFL on their future plans. The league had previously entertained input on the possibility of moving from a fall schedule to the spring.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ufl-football.com/spring |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 27, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120163826/http://www.ufl-football.com/spring |archivedate=January 20, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[Michael Huyghue]], the UFL's original commissioner, resigned from the position on January 31, 2012, citing in part the league's severe financial problems and philosophical differences with the league's owners on how to move forward.<ref>[http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=4349286 \"United Football League Commissioner Resigns,\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504070906/http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=4349286 |date=2012-05-04 }} press release from UFL via OurSportsCentral, 1/31/2012</ref><ref>Carp, Steve (January 31, 2012). [http://www.lvrj.com/sports/ufl-commissioner-huyghue-steps-down-138436434.html UFL commissioner Huyghue steps down] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513103206/http://www.lvrj.com/sports/ufl-commissioner-huyghue-steps-down-138436434.html |date=2012-05-13 }}. ''Las Vegas Review-Journal''. Retrieved January 31, 2012.</ref> Instead, the league dispensed, at least for the time being, with a central office and owners [[Bill Hambrecht]] ([[Las Vegas Locomotives|Las Vegas]]) and [[Bill Mayer]] ([[Virginia Destroyers|Virginia]]) oversee the league's business operations, while Locos' coach/president [[Jim Fassel]] oversees football operations.<ref name=LVRJ-04072012/> Before the fourth season starts, a rebuilding and restocking of personnel will need to take place. To conserve much-needed funds the [[Virginia Destroyers]] relocated to much smaller office space by February 2012.<ref>[http://hamptonroads.com/2012/02/destroyers-close-office-space-and-get-harder-find \"Destroyers close office space and get harder to find,\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508204216/http://hamptonroads.com/2012/02/destroyers-close-office-space-and-get-harder-find |date=2012-05-08 }} from ''The Virginian-Pilot'', 2/29/2012</ref> The league remained silent throughout winter, spring and early summer 2012, raising fears that the league had quietly folded, in the same way the proposed [[All American Football League]], without ever actually taking the field, had done in 2010 after repeated delays of its announced inaugural schedule.<ref>Pivovar, Steven (July 20, 2012). [https://archive.is/20130130232507/http://omaha.com/article/20120720/sports/307219987 Report: Nighthawks plan return with UFL]. ''Omaha World-Herald''. Retrieved July 26, 2012.</ref> However, on July 26, 2012, news broke that the UFL would indeed play a fourth season in 2012. Terms had not been finalized, but initial plans called for four teams playing an eight-game schedule (which would require an unbalanced schedule) on Wednesdays and Fridays beginning September 19, 2012.<ref>Minium, Harry (July 26, 2012). [http://hamptonroads.com/2012/07/virginia-destroyers-say-theyll-play-games-fall Virginia Destroyers say they'll play games this fall] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022143304/http://hamptonroads.com/2012/07/virginia-destroyers-say-theyll-play-games-fall |date=2012-10-22 }}. ''The Virginian-Pilot''. Retrieved July 26, 2012.</ref>  The league did reach a deal to have their games broadcast on CBS sports.<ref name=tu72612>Dougherty, Pete (July 26, 2012). [http://blog.timesunion.com/sportsmedia/cbs-sports-network-to-air-ufl-games/10262/ CBS Sports Network to air UFL games] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20120728122236/http://blog.timesunion.com/sportsmedia/cbs-sports-network-to-air-ufl-games/10262/ |date=2012-07-28 }}. ''Times Union'' (Albany, New York). Retrieved July 26, 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adweek.com/news/television/cbs-sports-network-inks-ufl-deal-142226|title=CBS Sports Network Inks UFL Deal|website=adweek.com|accessdate=29 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304064240/http://www.adweek.com/news/television/cbs-sports-network-inks-ufl-deal-142226|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref>  On the league's official website [http://www.ufl-football.com] on August 1, 2012, an official schedule for 2012, with the September 19 starting date and each team playing an unbalanced, eight-game schedule was posted, matching the earlier speculation. As of that time, final postseason plans remained undecided; the date for the championship game, Friday, November 16, was set, although the location was not. Also left unanswered was the question of whether last season's unusual third-place game would be repeated. On September 6, a revised UFL schedule for 2012 was posted on the Omaha Nighthawks website [http://www.omahanighthawks.com] showing the season rescheduled to begin on Friday, September 28, and end on Saturday, December 1, along with the claim that CBS Sports Network was in full concordance with this revision.\n\nAll teams but Sacramento used the same home stadiums as in 2011; the Mountain Lions moved to the [[Minor League Baseball|Triple-A baseball]] stadium ([[Raley Field]]) of the Sacramento franchise of the [[Pacific Coast League]], the [[Sacramento River Cats]]. In addition, the Las Vegas Locomotives also negotiated backup plans with [[Cashman Field]] in Las Vegas,<ref>Forster, Chad (August 1, 2012). [http://lasvegas.cbslocal.com/2012/08/01/the-las-vegas-locos-to-return-for-a-4th-season/ The Las Vegas Locos to return for a 4th season] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817084827/http://lasvegas.cbslocal.com/2012/08/01/the-las-vegas-locos-to-return-for-a-4th-season/ |date=2012-08-17 }}. ''KXNT''. Retrieved August 21, 2012.</ref> although the team was able to play its first two home games at [[Sam Boyd Stadium]].\n\nOn October 20, 2012, after four weeks, continued financial shortfalls, an uncertain stadium situation in Las Vegas, and dramatically reduced attendances across all four markets, the UFL ceased operations for the remainder of the 2012 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadspin.com/5953455/the-united-football-league-is-too-broke-to-finish-the-season|title=The United Football League Is Too Broke To Finish The Season|first=Isaac|last=Rauch|website=deadspin.com|accessdate=29 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827080836/http://deadspin.com/5953455/the-united-football-league-is-too-broke-to-finish-the-season|archivedate=27 August 2016}}</ref> According to head of public relations Larry Weismann, the league intended on resuming the canceled schedule some time in spring 2013, with those games counting toward the 2012 season standings, then come back yet again for the next season in fall 2013.<ref>{{cite web |last=Katzowitz |first=Josh |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/blog/eye-on-football/20618826/ufl-suspends-rest-of-2012-season |title=UFL suspends rest of 2012 season |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |date=2008-06-11 |accessdate=2012-10-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130516173608/http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/blog/eye-on-football/20618826/ufl-suspends-rest-of-2012-season |archivedate=2013-05-16 }}</ref>\n\n===2013===\n{{outdated|section|date=December 2019}}\nBy spring 2013, 78 players from the 2012 season, two head coaches from 2011 and four assistant coaches from the 2012 season had sued the league ownership for failure to pay their salaries. The Destroyers' business license expired on March 1, 2013, and that team's remaining offices were closed before that date.<ref name=teamofficecloses>{{cite news|title= Fans still waiting for Virginia Destroyer ticket refunds|url= http://www.wvec.com/my-city/vabeach/Still-no-refunds-for-Virginia-Destroyer-ticket-holders-190759331.html|date= February 11, 2013|accessdate= May 7, 2013|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130407203852/http://www.wvec.com/my-city/vabeach/Still-no-refunds-for-Virginia-Destroyer-ticket-holders-190759331.html|archivedate= April 7, 2013}}</ref> On March 28, 2013, a report in ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' noted that both the spring 2013 resumption and the fall 2013 season were canceled, and that if the league were to return, it would not have been until spring 2014 at the earliest.<ref>Adamson, Scott (May 5, 2013). [http://www.independentmail.com/news/2013/may/05/minor-league-football-didnt-spring-forward-promise/ Minor league football didn\u2019t spring forward as promised] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607062107/http://www.independentmail.com/news/2013/may/05/minor-league-football-didnt-spring-forward-promise/ |date=June 7, 2013 }}. ''Independent Mail'' (Anderson, South Carolina). Retrieved June 10, 2013.</ref>\n\n===Aftermath===\nAs of 2016, all of the remaining non-liquid assets of the league sit in a warehouse in [[Jacksonville, Florida]], with an estimated value of $100,000. The ownership lost or settled most of the lawsuits against them in 2014.<ref name=\"Kasler\">Dale Kasler, [http://www.sacbee.com/news/business/article54798225.html Ex-NFL coach fighting owners of defunct Sacramento team over $1 million in back pay] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221061338/http://www.sacbee.com/news/business/article54798225.html |date=2016-12-21}}, ''Sacramento Bee'' (January 14, 2016).</ref> The league still owes approximately $1,000,000 to the estate of [[Dennis Green]]; under a court ruling, the league itself is liable for Green's salary, as the owners had not personally guaranteed it.<ref name=\"Kasler\"/> Hambrecht has also allegedly not paid the 78 players who sued him for back pay, even as the players won a $2.4 million judgment against Hambrecht.<ref name=\"Kasler\"/> Frank Vuono, an executive with the UFL in its early existence, stated that Hambrecht had simply stopped paying the league's bills.<ref name=xflcomeback>Kaplan, Daniel and John Ourand (January 29, 2018). [https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2018/01/29/Leagues-and-Governing-Bodies/XFL.aspx A comeback for XFL, but can it win?] ''Sports Business Journal''. Retrieved January 19, 2019. Sidebar: \"So you want to start a pro football league?\"</ref>\n\nThe UFL abandoned its trademarks by 2017, when [[Vince McMahon]] filed a trademark on the United Football League name. In 2018, he instead announced a new [[XFL (2020)|XFL]], a brand used by McMahon's [[XFL (2001)|defunct football league]] that played one season in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadspin.com/timing-of-trademarks-suggests-new-xfl-may-be-a-respon-1821393884|title=Timing Of Trademarks Suggests \"New XFL\" May Be A Response To NFL Protests|first=David|last=Bixenspan|work=Deadspin.com|date=December 19, 2017|access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\nSix teams played in the UFL over the course of its history, no more than five in any given year. The teams that played in the league were: the [[Las Vegas Locomotives]], [[Hartford Colonials]] (originally the New York Sentinels), [[Omaha Nighthawks]], [[Sacramento Mountain Lions]] (originally the California Redwoods), Florida Tuskers, and [[Virginia Destroyers]]. The Florida Tuskers and Virginia Destroyers were legally separate teams, but because the Tuskers folded before the Destroyers began play, the UFL assigned most of the Tuskers' staff to the Destroyers and the two are typically conflated for the purpose of league history. \n\nOnly stadiums in which the team played more than one game are listed.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Team\n! scope=\"col\"| Metro area\n! scope=\"col\"| Stadium <span style=\"font-weight:normal;\">(capacity)</span>\n! scope=\"col\"| Years active\n! scope=\"col\"| Last coach\n! scope=\"col\"| Primary owner\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Florida Tuskers]]\n| [[Orlando, Florida]]\n| [[Camping World Stadium|Citrus Bowl]] (65,438)\n|align=center | 2009&ndash;10\n| [[Jay Gruden]]\n| [[Stuart Sternberg]] (2009)<br>[[Joe Theismann]] (2010)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Hartford Colonials]]<ref>Known as the ''New York Sentinels'' in 2009</ref>\n| [[Hartford, Connecticut]]\n| [[Rentschler Field (stadium)|Rentschler Field]] (40,000)\n|align=center | 2009&ndash;10\n| [[Jerry Glanville]]\n| [[Bill Mayer]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Las Vegas Locomotives]]\n| [[Las Vegas|Las Vegas, Nevada]]\n| [[Sam Boyd Stadium]] (36,800)\n|align=center | 2009&ndash;12\n| [[Jim Fassel]]\n| [[Bill Hambrecht]] & [[Rob Ryan (businessman)|Rob Ryan]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Omaha Nighthawks]]\n| [[Omaha, Nebraska]]\n| [[Rosenblatt Stadium]] (24,000)<br>[[TD Ameritrade Park]] (24,000)\n|align=center | 2010&ndash;12\n| [[Bart Andrus]]\n| [[Zach Nelson]] (2010)<br>Bill Hambrecht (2011\u20132012)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Sacramento Mountain Lions]]<ref>Known as the ''California Redwoods'' in 2009</ref>\n| [[Sacramento, California]]\n| [[AT&T Park]] (41,000)<br>[[Hornet Stadium (Sacramento)|Hornet Stadium]] (21,000)<br>[[Raley Field]] (14,014)\n|align=center | 2009&ndash;12\n| [[Turk Schonert]]\n| [[Paul Pelosi]]<ref>Minority shares held by [[George Zimmer]] and [[Angelo Tsakopoulos]]</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Virginia Destroyers]]\n| [[Virginia Beach, Virginia]]\n| [[Virginia Beach Sportsplex]] (14,000)\n|align=center | 2011&ndash;12\n| [[Kurt Schottenheimer]]\n| [[Bill Mayer]] (2012)<ref>[[Jim Speros]] was originally listed as owner but left before the team began play. Bill Hambrecht controlled the team in 2011.</ref>\n|}\n\n===Timeline===\n<timeline>\nDateFormat = mm/dd/yyyy\nImageSize  = width:800 height:auto barincrement:20\nPeriod     = from:08/01/2009 till:10/19/2012\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal\nPlotArea   = right:30 left:0 bottom:50 top:5\n\nColors = \n         id:line     value:black\n         id:bg       value:white\n\nPlotData=\n  width:15 textcolor:black shift:(5,-5) anchor:from fontsize:s\n\n  bar:1  color:yelloworange from:10/08/2009 till:11/27/2009 text:[[2009 UFL season|2009 season]]\n  bar:1  color:yelloworange from:09/17/2010 till:11/27/2010 text:[[2010 UFL season|2010 season]]\n  bar:1  color:yelloworange from:09/15/2011 till:10/21/2011 text:[[2011 UFL season|2011 season]]\n  bar:1  color:yelloworange from:09/19/2012 till:10/19/2012 text:[[2012 UFL season|2012 season]]\n  bar:2  color:kelleygreen from:08/01/2009 till:02/22/2010 text:[[New York Sentinels|NY Sentinels]] (09)\n  bar:2  color:purple from:02/23/2010 till:08/10/2011 text:[[Hartford Colonials]] (2010)