]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} {{sortname|Shaun|Murphy|Shaun Murphy (snooker player)}}\n| align=\"center\"|0\u20134\n|}\n\n===Variant finals: 1 (1 title)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:80px;\"|Outcome\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|No.\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:50px;\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:200px;\"|Championship\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:200px;\"|Opponent in the final\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"text-align:center; width:50px;\"|Score\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 1.\n| [[2010 Six-red World Championship|2010]]\n| [[Six-red World Championship]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} {{sortname|Ricky|Walden}}\n| align=\"center\"|8\u20136\n|}\n\n===Pool finals: 2 (1 title, 1 runner-up)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:80px;\"|Outcome\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20px;\"|No.\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:50px;\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:200px;\"|Championship\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:200px;\"|Opponent in the final\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"text-align:center; width:50px;\"|Score\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner\n| 1.\n| 2006\n| {{nowrap|[[World Eight-ball Pool Federation|WEPF]] [[List of world eight-ball champions|World Eight-ball Championship]]}}\n| {{Flagicon|ENG}} {{sortname|Darren|Appleton}}\n| align=\"center\"|11\u20137\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up\n| 1.\n| 2015\n| {{nowrap|Chinese Pool World Championship {{small|([[:de:Chinese 8-Ball World Championship 2015|de]])}}}}\n| {{Flagicon|ENG}} {{sortname|Darren|Appleton}}\n| align=\"center\"|19\u201321\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://www.markselby.info/}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111007042030/http://www.mark-selby.cz/ Website Mark Selby]\n*[http://www.worldsnooker.com/players/mark-selby-2/ Mark Selby] at ''worldsnooker.com''\n* [http://eurosport.yahoo.com/snooker/mark-selby/ Mark Selbys Blog on Eurosport]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090917113325/http://www.global-snooker.com/Mark-Selby.asp Profile on the Global Snooker]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121227015225/http://www.livingsnooker.com/blogs/mark-selby Mark Selbys Blog on LivingSnooker]\n* [http://www.snookerdatabase.co.uk/PlayerDetails.aspx?playerKey=6 Profile on Snooker Database]\n\n{{World snooker champions}}\n{{Snooker world number ones}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Selby, Mark}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Leicester]]\n[[Category:English snooker players]]\n[[Category:English pool players]]\n[[Category:Masters (snooker) champions]]\n[[Category:World champions in pool]]\n[[Category:World champions in snooker]]\n[[Category:World number one snooker players]]\n[[Category:UK champions (snooker)]]\n[[Category:People from Leicester]]\n[[Category:Winners of the professional snooker world championship]]\n[[Category:People from Oadby and Wigston (district)]]\n[[Category:World Snooker Hall of Fame inductees]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the American musician|Mark Selby (musician)}}\n{{short description|English professional snooker player, 3-time world champion (2014, 2016, 2017)}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n| name = Mark Selby\n| image = Mark Selby PHC 2016.jpg\n| caption = Paul Hunter Classic 2016\n| Nickname = Jester from Leicester<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/snooker/10817637/Mark-Selby-snookers-so-called-Jester-from-Leicester-is-having-a-laugh-with-his-nickname.html |title=Mark Selby, snooker's so-called Jester from Leicester, is having a laugh with his nickname |date=2014-05-08 |first=Matthew |last=Norman |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref name=Independent20110109>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/others/snooker-fate-starts-to-smile-on-the-leicester-jester-2179660.html |title=Snooker: Fate starts to smile on the Leicester Jester |first=Hector |last=Nunns |date=2011-01-09 |website=[[The Independent|independent.co.uk]] |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1983|6|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Leicester]], [[Leicestershire]], [[England]]\n| Sport country = {{ENG}}\n| Professional = 1999\u2013\n| High ranking = '''[[List of world number one snooker players|1]]''' {{smaller|(September 2011\u2013November 2012, December 2012\u2013February 2013, April\u2013June 2013, May\u2013July 2014, August\u2013December 2014, February 2015\u2013March 2019)}}\n| Prize money = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]5,316,908\n| High break = '''[[Maximum break|147]]''' {{smaller|(3 times)}}<ref name=\"worldsnooker.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/wpbsa/official-147s/ |title=Official 147s |work=World Snooker |accessdate=8 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121161058/http://www.worldsnooker.com/wpbsa/official-147s/ |archive-date=21 November 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| Century break = 625\n| Ranking wins = 17\n| Minor wins = 7\n| Other wins = 8\n| World champ = {{Hlist|[[2014 World Snooker Championship|2014]] | [[2016 World Snooker Championship|2016]] | [[2017 World Snooker Championship|2017]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Mark Anthony Selby''' (born 19 June 1983) is an English professional [[snooker]] player. He has been [[List of world snooker champions|World Snooker Champion]] three times and was number one in the [[Snooker world rankings|world rankings]] for over four years continuously. He has won 17 ranking titles, which puts him in joint seventh place (with [[Judd Trump]]) by ranking tournament wins in history.\n\nSelby joined the [[World Snooker Tour#Main Tour|main professional snooker tour]] in 1999 at the age of 16, after competing on the [[Challenge Tour (snooker)|UK Tour]] in 1998. He was runner-up to [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] at the [[2007 World Snooker Championship]]. He was the sixth player to win all of snooker's [[Triple Crown (snooker)|Triple Crown]] events at least twice, having won three [[Masters (snooker)|Masters]] titles ([[2008 Masters (snooker)|2008]], [[2010 Masters (snooker)|2010]], and [[2013 Masters (snooker)|2013]]), two [[UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championships]] ([[2012 UK Championship (snooker)|2012]] and [[2016 UK Championship|2016]]), and three [[World Snooker Championship|World Championships]] ([[2014 World Snooker Championship|2014]], [[2016 World Snooker Championship|2016]], and [[2017 World Snooker Championship|2017]]). His other ranking titles include the [[Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]] in [[2008 Welsh Open (snooker)|2008]], the [[Shanghai Masters (snooker)|Shanghai Masters]] in [[2011 Shanghai Masters|2011]], the [[German Masters]] in [[2015 German Masters|2015]], the [[China Open (snooker)|China Open]] in [[2015 China Open (snooker)|2015]], [[2017 China Open (snooker)|2017]], and [[2018 China Open (snooker)|2018]], the [[Paul Hunter Classic]] in [[2016 Paul Hunter Classic|2016]], the [[International Championship]] in [[2016 International Championship|2016]] and [[2017 International Championship|2017]], the [[China Championship (snooker)|China Championship]] in [[2018 China Championship|2018]], the [[English Open (snooker)|English Open]] in [[2019 English Open (snooker)|2019]], and the [[Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]] also in [[2019 Scottish Open (snooker)|2019]].\n\nKnown as a patient, tough competitor with strong safety play, Selby is also a prolific break-builder and has compiled over 600 [[century break]]s in his professional career. His [[List of snooker player nicknames|nickname]], \"The Jester from Leicester\", was given to him by snooker [[Master of ceremonies|compere]] Richard Beare. Selby is also a [[Pool (cue sports)|pool]] player. He was the 2006 [[World Eight-ball Pool Federation|WEPF]] [[eight-ball pool]] [[List of world eight-ball champions|world champion]] and was the 2015 Chinese Pool World Championship runner-up.\n\n== Early life ==\nSelby was born in [[Leicester]], England. He began playing pool at age eight and snooker aged nine.<ref name=Guardian2014>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/may/06/mark-selby-fulfilled-promise-to-dying-father |title=Mark Selby says snooker world title win fulfils promise made to late father |date=2014-05-06 |first=Paul |last=Weaver |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Malcolm Thorne, the brother of Leicester-born snooker player [[Willie Thorne]], spotted Selby's snooker ability and gave him free practice at his brother's snooker club, which Selby took full advantage of, practising in the evenings after school.<ref name=Guardian2014 /><ref name=RTE2014>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2014/0507/615692-s/ |title=Mark Selby reveals the path he took to becoming world champion |date=2014-05-07 |website=[[RT\u00c9.ie]] |access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\nWhen Selby was 16, his father David died of cancer.<ref name=RTE2014 /> Two months later, Selby joined the main professional tour,<ref name=BBCSport050514 /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/others/snooker-world-championship-mark-selby-toasts-his-maiden-win-with-iron-maiden-9328162.html |title=Snooker World Championship: Mark Selby toasts his maiden win... with Iron Maiden |first=Neil |last=Goulding |date=6 May 2014 |work=The Independent |accessdate=7 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508042933/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/others/snooker-world-championship-mark-selby-toasts-his-maiden-win-with-iron-maiden-9328162.html |archive-date=8 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> having left school with no qualifications.<ref name=RTE2014 />\n\n==Snooker career==\n\n===1998\u20132006===\nSelby showed potential as a teenager, but did not play snooker at a consistent level until his twenties. He began his career in 1998 on the [[Challenge Tour (snooker)|UK Tour]],{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} which was at that time the WPBSA's [[World Snooker Tour#Secondary professional tour|secondary professional tour]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/challenge.html |title=Brief History of the UK / Challenge Tour |year=2008 |first=Chris |last=Turner |work=Chris Turner's Snooker Archive |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228200859/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/challenge.html |archive-date=28 February 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> He joined the professional tour a year later at the age of 16.<ref name=Independent20110109 /><ref name=BBCSport050514>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/27289110 |title=Mark Selby dedicates World Championship title to late father |date=5 May 2014 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=18 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403004858/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/27289110 |archive-date=3 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In early 2002, he reached the semi-finals of the [[2002 China Open (snooker)|China Open]], despite leaving his hotel room at 2 a.m. instead of 2 p.m. for one of his matches because of [[jetlag]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/worldchampionships2005/profiles/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=Sporting_Life/05/03/31/manual_113935.html |title=World Snooker Player Profiles: Mark Selby |work=Sporting Life |location=UK |accessdate=22 December 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716121945/http://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/worldchampionships2005/profiles/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=Sporting_Life%2F05%2F03%2F31%2Fmanual_113935.html |archivedate=16 July 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In April 2003, aged 19, he reached his first ranking final at the [[2003 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]], where he finished runner-up to [[David Gray (snooker player)|David Gray]] who won 9\u20137.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/0203/so2003_res.shtml |title=Regal Scottish Open 2003 |website=snooker.org |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> He progressed to the final round of qualifying at the World Snooker Championships in both [[2002 World Snooker Championship|2002]] and [[2003 World Snooker Championship|2003]], but failed to qualify for the knockout stages at the [[Crucible Theatre]] on both occasions.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nFrom late 2005, Selby was managed by former snooker professional and fellow Leicester resident Mukesh Parmar.<ref name=Independent20110109 /> He progressed to the main draw of the [[2005 World Snooker Championship|World Snooker Championship]] for the first time in 2005, losing 5\u201310 to [[John Higgins]] in the first round.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} Since making his Crucible debut, he has qualified for the main knockout stages of the tournament every year, including the [[2006 World Snooker Championship|2006 World Championship]], despite his final qualifying round opponent [[Robert Milkins]] making a [[Maximum break|147]]. He then faced Higgins in the first round again, this time defeating the reigning [[2005 Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]] and [[2006 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] champion 10\u20134,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2006/apr/17/snooker.worldsnookerchampionship2006 |title=Selby keeps his cool to send Higgins crashing out |date=2006-04-17 |first=Clive |last=Everton |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=2020-02-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140922044946/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2006/apr/17/snooker.worldsnookerchampionship2006 |archive-date=2014-09-22 |url-status=live}}</ref> before being eliminated in the second round by [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/4869790.stm |title=Full World Championship results |date=2006-05-02 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=2020-02-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060619131622/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/4869790.stm |archive-date=2006-06-19 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132011===\nIn the 2007 World Championship, Selby beat [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]] 10\u20137 in the first round, having won eight successive frames from being 0\u20135 behind.<ref name=bbc3>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/6590115.stm |title=Selby completes amazing comeback |accessdate=6 May 2007 |work=BBC Sport |date=25 April 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070429053723/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/6590115.stm |archive-date=29 April 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> He then defeated former World Champion [[Peter Ebdon]] 13\u20138, with five centuries (including three-in-a-row) to reach the quarter-finals.<ref name=bbc2>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/6605633.stm |title=Sizzling Selby knocks out Ebdon |accessdate=6 May 2007 |work=BBC Sport |date=30 April 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070504133856/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/6605633.stm |archive-date=4 May 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> He beat [[Ali Carter]] 13\u201312, from 11\u20138 up and 11\u201312 down, in a quarter-final match that lasted well over nine hours.<ref name=bbc4>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/6612799.stm |title=Selby finally shakes off Carter |accessdate=6 May 2007 |work=BBC Sport |date=2 May 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070507035850/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/6612799.stm |archive-date=7 May 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> He reached the final by defeating [[Shaun Murphy]] 17\u201316 from 14\u201316 down, in another deciding frame which he won thanks to a 64 break.<ref name=bbc5>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/6621799.stm |title=Selby pips Murphy to reach final |accessdate=6 May 2007 |work=BBC Sport |date=5 May 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609033311/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/6621799.stm |archive-date=9 June 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> Against Higgins in the final, Selby trailed 4\u201312 after the Sunday sessions, but won all six frames played in the third session on Monday afternoon before the players ran out of time due to the length of the frames. Thus he entered the final session only 10\u201312 down and closed to within one frame at 13\u201314, but eventually succumbed 13\u201318.<ref name=\"bbc1\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/6633177.stm |title=Higgins beats brave Selby in epic |accessdate=8 May 2007 |work=BBC Sport |date=8 May 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018131743/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/6633177.stm |archive-date=18 October 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHis performances earned him [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]110,000 (not far off half of his pre-tournament all-time earnings). It was noted by eventual world champion John Higgins, amongst others, in his victory speech, that Selby was the most improved player on the tour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://matchroomsport.com/articleDetail.asp?intArticleId=500 |title=Murphy and Selby join Championship Snooker |accessdate=16 November 2009 |work=[[Matchroom Sport]] |date=6 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504093838/http://matchroomsport.com/articleDetail.asp?intArticleId=500 |archivedate=4 May 2008}}</ref> These performances in the 2006/07 season earned Selby a place in the top 16 for the very first time for the 2007\u201308 season, where he was ranked 11th.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/leicester/content/articles/2007/05/04/mark_selby_feature.shtml |title=Hot Shot |work=BBC Leicester |date=4 May 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513050451/https://www.bbc.co.uk/leicester/content/articles/2007/05/04/mark_selby_feature.shtml |archive-date=13 May 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSelby's wins over Lee, Ebdon, Carter and Murphy at the 2007 World Championships also won him the inaugural 888.com Silver Chip award for outstanding performance, awarded by the Snooker Writers' Association at the post-championship ball.<ref name=silverchipaward>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/news_press_releases-18703.htm |title=Selby's Had His Chip |work=World Snooker |date=5 May 2007 |accessdate=19 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070514012803/http://www.worldsnooker.com/news_press_releases-18703.htm |archivedate=14 May 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter a moderate start to the season, Selby had a strong run in the second-highest ranking tournament, the [[2007 UK Championship|UK Championship]], reaching the semi-finals of the event. He led eventual winner [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] 7\u20135, fell 7\u20138 behind, before levelling the match at 8\u20138. In the deciding frame, however, O'Sullivan made a 147 break to win 9\u20138.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=snooker/07/12/15/SNOOKER_Telford_Nightlead.html |title=Superb Sullivan stuns Selby |work=Sporting Life |location=UK |date=16 July 2011 |accessdate=22 December 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716122027/http://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=snooker%2F07%2F12%2F15%2FSNOOKER_Telford_Nightlead.html |archivedate=16 July 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:WSoS 2008 Moscow-204.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.8|Selby at the 2008 [[World Series of Snooker]] in Moscow]]\nOn 20 January 2008, Selby won his first major tournament \u2013 the [[2008 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] at [[Wembley]]. En route to the final, he had edged out [[Stephen Hendry]], [[Stephen Maguire]] and [[Ken Doherty]], all on a 6\u20135 scoreline (having been 3\u20135 behind against both Hendry and Maguire). In the final against Stephen Lee, after leading 5\u20133 at the break Selby took control and reeled off five consecutive frames (eight-in-a-row overall from 2\u20133 behind) to win convincingly 10\u20133. Selby's play in the final was of the highest standard, with four century breaks and two consecutive tons to cross the winning line. His final-frame effort, a total clearance of 141, equalled the tournament's highest break and was Selby's best in competitive play.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/7198650.stm |title=Selby trounces Lee to win Masters |date=20 January 2008 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=7 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820081547/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/7198650.stm |archive-date=20 August 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 17 February 2008, Selby won a close-fought [[2008 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]] final, overcoming Ronnie O'Sullivan 9\u20138 from 5\u20138 down.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/7249951.stm |title=Selby comeback stuns O'Sullivan |date=17 February 2008 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=7 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221210812/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/7249951.stm |archive-date=21 February 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, he could not reproduce his Crucible success from the previous season; despite going into the [[2008 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] as one of the bookmakers' favourites for the title, Selby was defeated 10\u20138 in the first round by [[Mark King (snooker player)|Mark King]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/apr/22/worldsnookerchampionship.snooker1 |title=King reigns supreme as Selby makes early exit |date=2008-04-22 |first=Les |last=Roopanarine |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=2020-02-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227040607/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/apr/22/worldsnookerchampionship.snooker1 |archive-date=2015-02-27 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe following year in the Welsh Open quarter-final, he was handed a writ by a member of the audience, supposedly his former manager George Barmby.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/7902914.stm |title=Writ claim disrupts Selby match |work=BBC Sport |date=20 February 2009 |accessdate=5 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223100438/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/7902914.stm |archive-date=23 February 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> Selby reached the final of the [[2009 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] again where he was runner-up to Ronnie O'Sullivan, and also reached the quarter-finals of the [[2009 World Snooker Championship|2009 World Championship]], losing 12\u201313 to Higgins, who again went on to win the title.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/may/04/john-higgins-world-snooker-championship-shaun-murphy1 |title=John Higgins beats Shaun Murphy to seal world championship title |date=2009-05-04 |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=2020-02-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927050932/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/may/04/john-higgins-world-snooker-championship-shaun-murphy1 |archive-date=2015-09-27 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe opened the [[2009\u201310 snooker season|2009\u201310 season]] with two first round defeats, before coming from 4\u20138 down to beat [[Jamie Cope]] 9\u20138 in the first round of the [[2009 UK Championship|UK Championship]], scoring six breaks of over 40 in those five frames.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/8399137.stm |title=Comeback win over Jamie Cope 'surprises' Mark Selby |date=2009-12-07 |first=Jonny |last=Bryan |work=BBC Sport |access-date=2020-02-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213132535/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/8399137.stm |archive-date=2009-12-13 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 January 2010, Selby won his second [[2010 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] title after reaching the final for the third time in as many years in a repeat of the previous year's final, where he lost to Ronnie O'Sullivan. O'Sullivan took a commanding lead at 9\u20136 leaving him just one frame from victory, but Selby played some of his best snooker of the season to overcome the three-frame deficit, taking the championship 10\u20139 and the \u00a3150,000 winner's cheque.<ref name=ukmasters2010>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/8464301.stm |title=Mark Selby shocks Ronnie O'Sullivan at Masters final |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=BBC Sport |date=18 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722061646/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/8464301.stm |archive-date=2010-07-22 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2011 China Open (snooker)|2011 China Open]], Selby beat [[Tian Pengfei]], [[Robert Milkins]], Ali Carter, and home favourite [[Ding Junhui]], but was defeated 8\u201310 by [[Judd Trump]] in the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=22&event=27 |title=China Open (2011) results |website=snooker.org |access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2011 World Snooker Championship|2011 World Championship]], Selby set the record for the most [[century break]]s compiled in a world championship match when he made six in his second round tie with Stephen Hendry.<ref>{{cite web |title=Selby rewrites the Crucible record books |date=24 April 2011 |work=World Snooker |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2345958,00.html |accessdate=24 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427230517/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~2345958%2C00.html |archivedate=27 April 2011}}</ref> It was also a record for a best-of-25 match and took Selby's century tally for the season to 54, setting a new record for the most centuries compiled in a season.<ref>{{cite news |work=BBC Sport |title=World Snooker: Selby beats Hendry to reach last eight |date=25 April 2011 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/13181061 |accessdate=24 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114160553/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/13181061 |archive-date=2016-01-14 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2011/2012===\n[[File:Mark Selby PHC 2011-1.jpg|thumb|2011 Paul Hunter Classic]]\nSelby started the [[2011\u201312 snooker season|2011\u201312 season]] by winning the non-ranking [[2011 Wuxi Classic|Wuxi Classic]] with a 9\u20137 victory over [[Ali Carter]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/Snooker-Mark-Selby-wins-Wuxi-Classic/story-12922096-detail/story.html |title=Snooker: Mark Selby wins Wuxi Classic |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |date=11 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507063342/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Snooker-Mark-Selby-wins-Wuxi-Classic/story-12922096-detail/story.html |archive-date=7 May 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> He continued his form at the [[2011 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]], where he won his second major ranking event by defeating [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] 10\u20139 in the final, having trailed 7\u20139.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/snooker/14870798.stm |title=Mark Selby beats Mark Williams to win Shanghai Masters |date=11 September 2011 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=12 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911215930/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/snooker/14870798.stm |archive-date=11 September 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nThe win also meant Selby usurped Williams as the world number one, making him the ninth player to hold the top spot and the first to do so without having previously won the World Championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://asia.eurosport.com/snooker/selby-downs-williams_sto2946252/story.shtml |title=Selby downs Williams |work=[[Eurosport]] |date=12 September 2011 |accessdate=1 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507013138/http://asia.eurosport.com/snooker/selby-downs-williams_sto2946252/story.shtml |archive-date=7 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nHe also won the minor-ranking [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Event 4|PTC Event 4]] (also known as the [[Paul Hunter Classic]]) with a 4\u20130 whitewash over [[Mark Davis (snooker player)|Mark Davis]], having edged out [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] 4\u20133 in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldsnooker.com/page/PTC4Article/0,,13165~2436238,00.html |title=Selby Storms To Title |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=30 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103045847/https://www.worldsnooker.com/page/PTC4Article/0,,13165~2436238,00.html |archive-date=3 January 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Selby would later finish 5th on the [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012#Order of Merit|Order of Merit]] and therefore qualified to the last 16 of the [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Finals|Finals]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2011 |title=Order of Merit |website=snooker.org |date=8 January 2012 |accessdate=31 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504060608/http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2011 |archive-date=4 May 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> He beat [[Ding Junhui]] in the Finals in [[Galway]] before losing 0\u20134 to eventual winner [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]] in the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Betfair Players Tour Championship Grand Finals (2012) |url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=103 |website=snooker.org |accessdate=18 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309225019/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=103 |archive-date=9 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSelby progressed to the quarter-finals of the [[2012 German Masters|German Masters]] and then reached the final of the [[2012 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], where he lost 6\u20139 to Ding.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/17091924 |title=Welsh Open: China's Ding Junhui beats Mark Selby 9\u20136 to lift title |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=19 February 2012 |accessdate=1 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301044623/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/17091924 |archive-date=1 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another semi-final followed in the [[2012 World Open (snooker)|World Open]] and despite seeing a 5\u20132 lead slip to a 5\u20136 defeat against [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]], he looked to be in form at just the right time in the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/17245308 |title=Mark Allen to face Stephen Lee in World Open final |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=3 March 2012 |accessdate=1 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305235804/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/17245308 |archive-date=5 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHowever, Selby was forced to withdraw from the second round of the [[2012 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] with a neck injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/29032012/58/selby-withdraws-china-open.html |title=Selby withdraws from China Open |work=[[Eurosport]] |date=29 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507050205/https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/29032012/58/selby-withdraws-china-open.html |archive-date=7 May 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> His withdrawal was also a precautionary measure to be ready for the upcoming [[2012 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], for which Selby declared himself fit the week before the event. He played [[Barry Hawkins]] in the first round and was beaten 3\u201310. After the match Selby admitted he had only managed nine hours of practice in the lead up and that there were certain shots he was physically unable to play.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/sport/other-sports/mark-selby-equals-unwanted-record-7681104.html |title=Mark Selby equals unwanted record |newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=26 April 2012 |accessdate=1 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507014827/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/sport/other-sports/mark-selby-equals-unwanted-record-7681104.html |archive-date=7 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite the disappointing end to the season Selby was guaranteed to end it ranked number one following [[Judd Trump]]'s early exit from the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0,,13165~176157,00.pdf |title=Official World Snooker Ranking List for the 2012/2013 Season |date=8 May 2012 |work=World Snooker |accessdate=23 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616125200/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0%2C%2C13165~176157%2C00.pdf |archivedate=16 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mark Selby Sieger PHC 2012.jpg|thumb|upright|Selby with the [[European Tour 2012/2013 \u2013 Event 1|2012 Paul Hunter Classic]] trophy]]\n\n===2012/2013===\nSelby announced he was \"90% fit\" just before the start of the [[Snooker season 2012/2013|2012/2013 season]] as he continued his recovery from the disc bulge in his neck.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/Snooker-Mark-Selby-90-cent-fit-raring/story-16438875-detail/story.html |title=Snooker: Mark Selby '90 per cent fit and raring to go' |newspaper=Leicester Mercury |date=23 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507045327/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Snooker-Mark-Selby-90-cent-fit-raring/story-16438875-detail/story.html |archive-date=7 May 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> His first event was the [[2012 Wuxi Classic|Wuxi Classic]] where, ironically, he played Hawkins in the last 32. Selby this time won 5\u20132 and then breezed past [[Jamie Cope]] 5\u20130 to set up a quarter-final match with in-form [[Stuart Bingham]], which Selby lost 4\u20135.<ref name=\"2012/13\">{{cite web |url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=17&season=2012 |title=Mark Selby 2012/2013 |website=snooker.org |accessdate=13 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711014543/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=17&season=2012 |archive-date=11 July 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2827261,00.html |title=In Form Bingham Keeps Run Going |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=29 June 2012 |first=Matt |last=Rich |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702031642/https://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2827261,00.html |archive-date=2 July 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Selby then won seven matches in a row in reaching the quarter-finals of the [[2012 Six-red World Championship|Six-red World Championship]], but there he lost 5\u20137 by [[Judd Trump]].<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> He then suffered a shock 3\u20135 first round defeat to [[Jamie Burnett]] in the [[2012 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2840595,00.html |title=Brilliant Burnett Knocks Out Selby |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=11 July 2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120714043906/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~2840595%2C00.html |archivedate=14 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/18795253 |title=Australian Open 2012: Mark Selby loses to Jamie Burnett |date=11 July 2012 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815040554/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/18795253 |archive-date=15 August 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSelby lost his world number one spot to Judd Trump after the latter's victory in the inaugural [[International Championship]] in China. However, just five weeks later, Selby won his third ranking title and largest of his career, the [[2012 UK Championship|UK Championship]], to regain the top spot. He defeated [[Michael White (snooker player)|Michael White]] 6\u20133, [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]] 6\u20134 from 0\u20133 down, and [[Neil Robertson]] 6\u20134 from 0\u20134 down to reach the semi-finals, where he beat [[Mark Davis (snooker player)|Mark Davis]] 9\u20134 to progress to the final. Already assured of overtaking Trump regardless of the result, Selby beat his good friend [[Shaun Murphy]] 10\u20136 to win the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |title=UK Snooker Championship 2012: Mark Selby beats Shaun Murphy |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/20658965 |date=10 December 2012 |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=21 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121216015941/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/20658965 |archive-date=16 December 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSelby also participated at the [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013|Players Tour Championship]]. He successfully defended his [[European Tour 2012/2013 \u2013 Event 1|Paul Hunter Classic]] title with a 4\u20131 win over [[Joe Swail]] in the final.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2901339,00.html |title=Selby Retains Classic Title |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=26 August 2012 |accessdate=27 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120828061825/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2901339,00.html |archive-date=28 August 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> He then lost in the final of the [[European Tour 2012/2013 \u2013 Event 2|Antwerp Open]] 1\u20134 against [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Allen Blasts Three Tons in Antwerp Final |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2955533,00.html |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=21 October 2012 |accessdate=27 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027025106/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2955533,00.html |archive-date=27 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and won the [[European Tour 2012/2013 \u2013 Event 6|Munich Open]] by defeating [[Graeme Dott]] 3\u20134 in the final.<ref>{{cite web |title=Betfair European Tour 6 (Munich Open 2013) draw |url=http://3a43ed9bbf8e4c3a0092-e5ae3e47d460213726cd286f2f322a12.r38.cf3.rackcdn.com/a7cee6b40b9674249b0b0d5b6430f95db_Print.pdf |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=7 January 2013 |accessdate=6 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507031837/http://3a43ed9bbf8e4c3a0092-e5ae3e47d460213726cd286f2f322a12.r38.cf3.rackcdn.com/a7cee6b40b9674249b0b0d5b6430f95db_Print.pdf |archivedate=7 May 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> He then finished number one on the [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013#Order of Merit|Order of Merit]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Order of Merit issued after Munich Open 2013 (ET6) |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/7a/ba/0,,13165~178810,00.pdf |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=7 January 2013 |accessdate=7 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127034421/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/7a/ba/0%2C%2C13165~178810%2C00.pdf |archivedate=27 January 2013}}</ref> and qualified for the [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013 \u2013 Finals|Finals]], where he lost 3\u20134 against [[Jack Lisowski]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2013 Dafabet PTC Grand Final results |url=http://3a43ed9bbf8e4c3a0092-e5ae3e47d460213726cd286f2f322a12.r38.cf3.rackcdn.com/3b0b79e1-b7a0-4dcd-9a5d-5f1445afd017.pdf |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=17 March 2013 |accessdate=17 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507031842/http://3a43ed9bbf8e4c3a0092-e5ae3e47d460213726cd286f2f322a12.r38.cf3.rackcdn.com/3b0b79e1-b7a0-4dcd-9a5d-5f1445afd017.pdf |archivedate=7 May 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mark Selby at Snooker German Masters (DerHexer) 2013-01-30 16.jpg|thumb|2013 German Masters]]\nSelby then went on to win his third [[2013 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] title, beating Stuart Bingham 6\u20135 from 1\u20135 behind in the first round, [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] 6\u20131 in the quarter-finals, and Graeme Dott 6\u20135 from 1\u20134 and 4\u20135 down in the semi-finals. He then defeated defending champion Neil Robertson 10\u20136 in the final.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hafez |first=Shamoon |title=Masters snooker final 2013: Mark Selby beats Neil Robertson |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/21110882 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=21 January 2013 |accessdate=1 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123002647/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/21110882 |archive-date=23 January 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> He reached the quarter-finals of the [[2013 German Masters|German Masters]], but lost 1\u20135 against [[Barry Hawkins]].<ref>{{cite web |title=German Masters 2013: Schedule and results from Berlin |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/21253174 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=2 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201142207/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/21253174 |archive-date=1 February 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> He lost in the last 32 of the [[2013 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]] 0\u20134 against [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Welsh Open 2013: Schedule and results from Newport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/21402731 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=16 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216003945/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/21402731 |archive-date=16 February 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> and lost his number one position to Trump.<ref>{{cite web |title=Updated Rankings \u2013 Trump Back on Top |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3081190,00.html |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=19 February 2013 |accessdate=19 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130222045653/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~3081190%2C00.html |archivedate=22 February 2013}}</ref> Selby then reached the quarter-finals of the [[2013 World Open (snooker)|World Open]], but lost 3\u20135 against Neil Robertson.<ref>{{cite web |title=Haikou Open 2013: Schedule and results from China |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/21524925 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=25 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227170152/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/21524925 |archive-date=27 February 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2013 China Open (snooker)|China Open]], Selby became only the fourth player in history to miss the final black on a 147 attempt, and only the second \u2013 after [[Ken Doherty]] \u2013 to do so in a televised match, in a 5\u20131 defeat of [[Mark King (snooker player)|Mark King]].<ref>{{cite web |title=China Open: Mark Selby misses final black on 147 attempt |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/21953344 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=27 March 2013 |accessdate=1 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330004130/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/21953344 |archive-date=30 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Selby Through Despite Black Blunder |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3123662,00.html |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=27 March 2013 |accessdate=1 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330092057/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~3123662%2C00.html |archivedate=30 March 2013}}</ref> He then reached the final by defeating [[Ricky Walden]] 5\u20132, Mark Williams 5\u20131 and Murphy 6\u20132, but lost 6\u201310 against Neil Robertson.<ref>{{cite web |title=2013 China Open results |url=http://3a43ed9bbf8e4c3a0092-e5ae3e47d460213726cd286f2f322a12.r38.cf3.rackcdn.com/c585315d-822c-43f9-89d9-c59ee6641d20.pdf |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=31 March 2013 |accessdate=31 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411224738/http://3a43ed9bbf8e4c3a0092-e5ae3e47d460213726cd286f2f322a12.r38.cf3.rackcdn.com/c585315d-822c-43f9-89d9-c59ee6641d20.pdf |archivedate=11 April 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> After the event he regained the number one spot from Trump. He finished off the season at the [[2013 World Snooker Championship]], where he beat [[Matthew Selt]] 10\u20134 in the first round,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/22284902 |title=World Snooker Championship 2013: Mark Selby goes through |date=2013-04-24 |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |work=BBC Sport |access-date=2020-02-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227195451/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/22284902 |archive-date=2020-02-27 |url-status=live}}</ref> before losing 10\u201313 to eventual runner-up Barry Hawkins in the second round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/22322954 |title=World Snooker Championship 2013: Hawkins knocks out Selby |date=2013-04-27 |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |work=BBC Sport |access-date=2020-02-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010214024/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/22322954 |archive-date=2018-10-10 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2013/2014===\nSelby started the [[2013\u201314 snooker season|season]] with a 3\u20135 defeat to [[Andrew Pagett]] in the qualifying rounds of the [[2013 Wuxi Classic]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/22682698 |title=Mark Selby suffers Wuxi Classic defeat by Andrew Pagett |accessdate=1 June 2013 |date=27 May 2013 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011105543/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/22682698 |archive-date=11 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The tournament was the first to use a new format requiring the top 16 players to compete in the qualifying rounds. In minor-ranking tournaments, he was runner-up in the [[Asian Tour 2013/2014 \u2013 Event 1|Yixing Open]], where he lost 1\u20134 to [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://au.eurosport.com/snooker/perry-downs-selby-to-claim-yixing-title_sto3803588/story.shtml |title=Perry downs Selby to claim Yixing title |date=16 June 2013 |work=[[Eurosport]] |access-date=18 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507012939/http://au.eurosport.com/snooker/perry-downs-selby-to-claim-yixing-title_sto3803588/story.shtml |archive-date=7 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the [[European Tour 2013/2014 \u2013 Event 2|Rotterdam Open]], where he lost 3\u20134 to [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12243/8834960/rotterdam-open-mark-williams-beats-mark-selby-in-final-to-end-title-drought |title=Rotterdam Open: Mark Williams beats Mark Selby in final to end title drought |date=21 July 2013 |work=[[Sky Sports]] |access-date=18 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507030813/http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12243/8834960/rotterdam-open-mark-williams-beats-mark-selby-in-final-to-end-title-drought |archive-date=7 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> In November, he won the [[European Tour 2013/2014 \u2013 Event 7|Antwerp Open]], defeating [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] 4\u20133 in the final.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12243/9029711/mark-selby-beats-ronnie-osullivan-in-antwerp-open-final |title=Mark Selby beats Ronnie O'Sullivan in Antwerp Open final |date=17 November 2013 |work=[[Sky Sports]] |access-date=18 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507030725/http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12243/9029711/mark-selby-beats-ronnie-osullivan-in-antwerp-open-final |archive-date=7 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[File:Mark Selby at Snooker German Masters (DerHexer) 2015-02-08 38.jpg|thumb|Selby at [[2014 German Masters]]]]\nAt the [[2013 UK Championship]] in December, in the seventh frame of his semi-final against [[Ricky Walden]], Selby compiled snooker's 100th officially recognised [[maximum break]] in professional competition.<ref name=\"worldsnooker.com\" /> He received \u00a355,000 for the achievement, in addition to the tournament's highest break prize of \u00a34,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=UK Snooker Championship 2013: Selby makes 100th 147 break |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/25284182 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=18 March 2014 |date=7 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140122193803/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/25284182 |archive-date=22 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> The next day, he lost 7\u201310 to [[Neil Robertson]] in the final, having been ahead 5\u20131 and 6\u20133.<ref>{{cite web |title=UK Snooker Championship 2013: Neil Robertson beats Mark Selby |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/25292566 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=18 March 2014 |date=8 December 2013 |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140205231845/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/25292566 |archive-date=5 February 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHe began the defence of his title at the [[2014 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] by defeating [[Mark Davis (snooker player)|Mark Davis]] in the first round and [[John Higgins]] in the quarter-finals, winning both matches 6\u20135 and extending his unbeaten record in deciding frames at the Masters to 11.<ref>{{cite web |title=Masters 2014: Mark Selby and John Higgins into quarter-finals |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/25705472 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=29 January 2014 |date=12 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113145624/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/25705472 |archive-date=13 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Masters 2014: Mark Selby beats John Higgins 6\u20135 in thriller |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/25761630 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=29 January 2014 |date=17 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116234030/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/25761630 |archive-date=16 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> He then beat [[Shaun Murphy]] 6\u20131 in the semi-finals to reach the final against Ronnie O'Sullivan.<ref>{{cite web |title=Masters 2014: Mark Selby to face Ronnie O'Sullivan in final |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/25795123 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=29 January 2014 |date=18 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201150450/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/25795123 |archive-date=1 February 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> After falling behind 1\u20137 in the first session, Selby lost the final 4\u201310, receiving the runner-up prize of \u00a390,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ronnie O'Sullivan wins fifth Masters title by beating Mark Selby |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/25802468 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=29 January 2014 |date=19 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201192233/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/25802468 |archive-date=1 February 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the [[2014 German Masters|German Masters]] two weeks later, he was eliminated in the second round by [[Kurt Maflin]] 5\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/25971664 |title=Mark Selby & Neil Robertson beaten at German Masters |date=2014-01-30 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> He defeated [[Alan McManus]] 5\u20131 in the quarter-finals of the [[2014 World Open (snooker)|World Open]], and [[Marco Fu]] 6\u20134 in the semi-finals, but lost 6\u201310 in the final to Shaun Murphy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/26601655 |title=Shaun Murphy holds off Mark Selby to win Haikou World Open |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=16 March 2014 |access-date=12 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924232812/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/26601655 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2014 World Snooker Championship|2014 World Championship]], Selby defeated [[Michael White (snooker player)|Michael White]] 10\u20139, [[Ali Carter]] 13\u20139, and Alan McManus 13\u20135 to reach his first semi-final at the Crucible since 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12243/9292135/world-championship-ronnie-osullivan-and-mark-selby-make-strong-start-to-semi-finals |title=World Championship: Ronnie O'Sullivan and Mark Selby made strong starts in semi-finals |work=[[Sky Sports]] |date=2 May 2014 |accessdate=6 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506095923/http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12243/9292135/world-championship-ronnie-osullivan-and-mark-selby-make-strong-start-to-semi-finals |archive-date=6 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> He faced world number one Neil Robertson in a repeat of the UK Championship final five months earlier, this time achieving a 17\u201315 victory in a match described by commentators as one of the best matches ever played in the tournament's history, to reach his second World Championship final and first for seven years.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/may/03/neil-robertson-mark-selby-world-snooker-championship |title=Mark Selby holds off Neil Robertson to reach final with Ronnie O'Sullivan |agency=Press Association |date=3 May 2014 |accessdate=13 January 2020 |newspaper=The Guardian |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113214202/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/may/03/neil-robertson-mark-selby-world-snooker-championship |archive-date=13 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> His opponent in the final was two-time defending champion Ronnie O'Sullivan, who had won all five of his previous world finals. O'Sullivan led 3\u20130, 8\u20133, and 10\u20135, but Selby then won six frames in a row to lead for the first time, eventually sealing an 18\u201314 victory for his first world title.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1140506/jsp/sports/story_18312087.jsp |title=Great fightback by Mark Selby \u2013 O'Sullivan loses five of the six frames |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph (India)]] |publisher=[[ABP Group]] |date=6 May 2014 |accessdate=6 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506202656/http://www.telegraphindia.com/1140506/jsp/sports/story_18312087.jsp |archive-date=6 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/27289016 |title=World Snooker Championship 2014: Mark Selby wins style battle |date=6 May 2014 |first=Ben |last=Dirs |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=6 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507025202/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/27289016 |archive-date=7 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Winning the World Championship, he became the ninth player to win snooker's [[Triple Crown (snooker)|Triple Crown]] of World, UK and Masters titles (and the second of the season after Robertson), and the twelfth player to win the World and UK Championship \"double\" in their career.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/27286638 |title=Mark Selby beats Ronnie O'Sullivan to win world title |date=5 May 2014 |first=Ben |last=Dirs |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=6 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506143710/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/27286638 |archive-date=6 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> With his World Championship victory, Selby also retook the world number one spot.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/snooker/sport/story/305333.html |title=Selby caps stunning comeback to win world title |publisher=[[ESPN (UK)|ESPN]] |date=5 May 2014 |accessdate=6 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506055557/http://www.espn.co.uk/snooker/sport/story/305333.html |archive-date=6 May 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2014/2015===\n[[File:German Masters 2015 champion Mark Selby with trophy (Martin Rulsch).jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Selby with [[2015 German Masters]] trophy]]\nAt the [[2014 Wuxi Classic|Wuxi Classic]], the first ranking event of the season, Selby lost 3\u20135 to [[Liang Wenbo]] in the last 32.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wuxi Classic: Mark Selby loses to Liang Wenbo in China |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/28027795 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=25 June 2014 |accessdate=1 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018015252/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/28027795 |archive-date=18 October 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> He won the minor-ranking [[European Tour 2014/2015 \u2013 Event 1|Riga Open]] in August, defeating [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] 4\u20133 in the final,<ref>{{cite web |title=Selby Takes Riga Title |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~4065459,00.html |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=10 August 2014 |accessdate=11 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812211721/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~4065459%2C00.html |archivedate=12 August 2014}}</ref> but lost 5\u20136 to Allen the following month in the semi-finals of the ranking [[2014 Shanghai Masters (snooker)|Shanghai Masters]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Shanghai Masters: Mark Allen to face Stuart Bingham in final |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/29189910 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=13 September 2014 |accessdate=1 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140916052803/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/29189910 |archive-date=16 September 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> He made an unexpected early exit from the ranking [[2014 International Championship|International Championship]] in the last 128, when 19-year-old tour rookie [[Oliver Lines]] recovered from 0\u20134 behind to defeat him 6\u20134.<ref>{{cite web |title=Selby Falls Behind Enemy Lines |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~4170432,00.html |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=25 September 2014 |accessdate=1 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030094340/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~4170432,00.html |archive-date=30 October 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> He reached the quarter-finals of the invitational [[2014 Champion of Champions|Champion of Champions]] tournament in November, but lost 1\u20136 against [[Judd Trump]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Trump sinks Selby title hopes |url=https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/article/663/9550300/champion-of-champions-snooker-judd-trump-thrashes-mark-selby| |work=[[Sporting Life (British newspaper)|Sporting Life]] |date=4 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141120073239/https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/article/663/9550300/champion-of-champions-snooker-judd-trump-thrashes-mark-selby |archive-date=20 November 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> He suffered another disappointment at the [[2014 UK Championship|UK Championship]], losing 4\u20136 to [[David Morris (snooker player)|David Morris]] in the last 64.<ref>{{cite web |title=UK Championship 2014: David Morris beats Mark Selby |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/30259291 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=29 November 2014 |accessdate=1 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141130210818/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/30259291 |archive-date=30 November 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn his first-round encounter with [[Shaun Murphy]] at the [[2015 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] in January, Selby fell 1\u20135 behind before recovering to tie the match at 5\u20135, but lost the deciding frame and the match 5\u20136. This was the first time he had ever lost a deciding frame at the Masters, having previously won 11.<ref>{{cite web |title=Masters 2015: Mark Selby beaten by Shaun Murphy in first round |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/30770807 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=11 January 2015 |accessdate=12 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150112165232/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/30770807 |archive-date=12 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The following month, he defeated Judd Trump 5\u20134 in the quarter-finals of the [[2015 German Masters|German Masters]]. During the match, Trump made his second career 147 and second against Selby; it was the fifth time that Selby had witnessed an opponent make a maximum break against him, the most of any player in the history of the game.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/German-Masters-Judd-Trump-racks-second-career-147/story-25990306-detail/story.html |title=German Masters: Judd Trump racks up second career 147 in quarter-final defeat to Mark Selby |date=7 February 2015 |first=Luke |last=Baker |newspaper=[[Bath Chronicle]] |accessdate=3 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518104823/http://www.bathchronicle.co.uk/German-Masters-Judd-Trump-racks-second-career-147/story-25990306-detail/story.html |archivedate=18 May 2015 }}</ref> He then beat [[Stephen Maguire]] 6\u20132 in the semi-finals to reach his first ranking final of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/31176105 |title=German Masters: Judd Trump hits maximum in defeat to Mark Selby |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=6 February 2015 |accessdate=5 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407042516/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/31176105 |archive-date=7 April 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> He came from 2\u20135 down against Sean Murphy to win the final 9\u20137 and claim the title.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/31263089 |title=Mark Selby beats Shaun Murphy to win German Masters title |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=8 February 2015 |accessdate=5 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150313102944/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/31263089 |archive-date=13 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2015 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] in April, Selby became the first player to win a second ranking title this season. He advanced to the final without facing any player inside the world's top 16, and then outplayed world number 56 [[Gary Wilson (snooker player)|Gary Wilson]] to win 10\u20132.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~4616182,00.html |title=Selby Storms to China Title |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=8 April 2015 |accessdate=5 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150410105617/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~4616182,00.html |archive-date=10 April 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> He therefore had two statistics against him in defence of his world title, as no first-time world champion has successfully defended the title the following year and no winner of the China Open has won the World Championship in the same season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12040/9805198/mark-selby-steels-himself-for-sheffield-defence-of-world-championship |title=Mark Selby steels himself for Sheffield defence of World Championship |work=[[Sky Sports]] |date=25 April 2015 |accessdate=29 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150503051223/http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12040/9805198/mark-selby-steels-himself-for-sheffield-defence-of-world-championship |archive-date=3 May 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> He led [[Kurt Maflin]] 8\u20134 in the first round, before his opponent reeled off five frames in a row, but Selby then took the 18th frame and the decider to win the match 10\u20139. His reign as World Champion ended in the second round, however,  with a 9\u201313 defeat to [[Anthony McGill]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/19/mark-selby-kurt-maflin-snooker-world-championship-sheffield-crucible |title=Mark Selby relies on instinct to survive Crucible scare against Kurt Maflin |date=19 April 2015 |agency=Press Association |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=29 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150505062536/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/19/mark-selby-kurt-maflin-snooker-world-championship-sheffield-crucible |archive-date=5 May 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/32459068 |title=Anthony McGill can win world snooker title, says Mark Selby |date=24 April 2015 |first=Owen |last=Phillips |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=29 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150429000637/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/32459068 |archive-date=29 April 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite this setback, he finished the season as world number one for the fourth year in a row.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Rankings After 2015 Betfred World Championship |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/rankings/ |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=8 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150507001308/http://www.worldsnooker.com/rankings/ |archivedate=7 May 2015 |url-status=unfit}}</ref>\n\n===2015/2016===\nSelby defeated [[Neil Robertson]] 6\u20134 in the quarter-finals of the [[2015 International Championship|International Championship]] to reach his first semi-final of the season, but then lost 4\u20139 to [[John Higgins]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/snooker/john-higgins-beats-mark-selby-to-reach-daqing-final-1-3934889 |title=John Higgins beats Mark Selby to reach Daqing final |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=2 November 2015 |accessdate=30 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819105451/http://www.scotsman.com/sport/snooker/john-higgins-beats-mark-selby-to-reach-daqing-final-1-3934889 |archive-date=19 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> He did not drop a frame in reaching the third round of the [[2015 UK Championship|UK Championship]] where he defeated [[Jamie Jones (snooker player)|Jamie Jones]] 6\u20135, later acknowledging that his opponent had deserved to win the match.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/14114176.UK_Championship__World_number_one_Mark_Selby_scrapes_through_in_final_frame_thriller_with_Jamie_Jones/ |title=UK Championship: World number one Mark Selby scrapes through in final frame thriller with Jamie Jones |date=1 December 2015 |first=Steve |last=Carroll |newspaper=[[The Press (York)|The Press]] |accessdate=30 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505130512/http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/14114176.UK_Championship__World_number_one_Mark_Selby_scrapes_through_in_final_frame_thriller_with_Jamie_Jones/ |archive-date=5 May 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> He then eliminated [[Dechawat Poomjaeng]] and [[Matthew Selt]] both 6\u20131, before being whitewashed 6\u20130 by Robertson in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/robertson-crushes-selby-in-york/ |title=Robertson Crushes Selby in York |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=5 December 2015 |accessdate=30 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816161752/http://www.worldsnooker.com/robertson-crushes-selby-in-york/ |archive-date=16 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In early 2016, Selby lost to [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in the quarter-finals of both the [[2016 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] and [[2016 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/ronnie-o-sullivan-masters-mark-selby-to-make-final-four-at-alexandra-palace_sto5059219/story.shtml |title=Ronnie O'Sullivan masters Mark Selby to make final four at Alexandra Palace |date=14 January 2016 |first=Toby |last=Keel |work=[[Eurosport]] |accessdate=30 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812230116/http://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/ronnie-o-sullivan-masters-mark-selby-to-make-final-four-at-alexandra-palace_sto5059219/story.shtml |archive-date=12 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/35544725 |title=Welsh Open 2016: Scores and results |work=BBC Sport |access-date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222135453/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/35544725 |archive-date=22 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> but won the [[European Tour 2015/2016 \u2013 Event 6|Gdynia Open]] with a 4\u20131 victory over [[Martin Gould]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snookerdatabase.co.uk/EventResults.aspx?EventKey=458 |title=2016 Gdynia Open Results |website=Snooker Database |access-date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705103448/http://www.snookerdatabase.co.uk/EventResults.aspx?EventKey=458 |archive-date=5 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn March, he withdrew from the [[2016 Players Tour Championship Final|PTC Finals]] and [[2016 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] for personal reasons,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://snookerhq.com/2016/03/18/selby-withdraws-from-players-championship-and-china-open/ |title=Selby Withdraws from Players Championship and China Open |first=David |last=Caulfield |date=2016-03-18 |website=SnookerHQ |access-date=2020-04-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322211313/https://snookerhq.com/2016/03/18/selby-withdraws-from-players-championship-and-china-open/ |archive-date=2016-03-22 |url-status=live}}</ref> missing out on the opportunity to defend his 2015 China Open title. Returning to the tour at the [[2016 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] in April, he beat [[Robert Milkins]] 10\u20136, [[Sam Baird]] 13\u201311, and [[Kyren Wilson]] 13\u20138, to face [[Marco Fu]] in the semi-finals. Selby drew level at 12\u201312 after winning a 76-minute frame, the longest in Crucible history, and won the match 17\u201315 with a successful snooker on the brown in the final frame.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/36177534 |title=World Snooker Championship: Mark Selby reaches the final |date=1 May 2016 |first=Owen |last=Phillips |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=31 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503043038/http://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/36177534 |archive-date=3 May 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> He took an early 6\u20130 lead over [[Ding Junhui]] in the final, eventually winning the match 18\u201314 to claim his second world title. With his World Championship victory, Selby finished at number one in the world rankings for the fifth consecutive year.<ref name=\"2016 WC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/36186995 |title=Mark Selby beats Ding Junhui to win World Snooker Championship |date=2 May 2016 |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=31 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502214204/http://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/36186995 |archive-date=2 May 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2016/2017===\n[[File:Mark Selby at 2016 European Masters.jpg|thumb|Selby at [[2016 European Masters]] in [[Bucharest]], Romania]]\nSelby won his first ranking title of the season at the [[2016 Paul Hunter Classic|Paul Hunter Classic]], defeating [[Tom Ford (snooker player)|Tom Ford]] 4\u20132 in the final.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/37210994 |title=Mark Selby wins snooker's Paul Hunter Classic in Germany |date=28 August 2016 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402112407/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/37210994 |archive-date=2 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> His semi-final with [[Stuart Bingham]] at the [[2016 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]] was a meeting between the top two ranked players in the world, Selby winning 6\u20135, having been 3\u20135 behind.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/selby-edges-bingham-to-reach-final/ |title=Selby Edges Bingham to Reach Final |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=24 September 2016 |accessdate=3 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161002214214/http://www.worldsnooker.com/selby-edges-bingham-to-reach-final/ |archive-date=2 October 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> After taking an early 3\u20131 advantage over [[Ding Junhui]] in the final, Selby eventually lost 10\u20136.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/37467459 |title=Shanghai Masters: Ding Junhui beats world champion Mark Selby in final |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=25 September 2016 |accessdate=3 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928053802/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/37467459 |archive-date=28 September 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was defeated 6\u20132 by [[Judd Trump]] in the semi-finals of the [[2016 European Masters|European Masters]].<ref name=\"2016/17\">{{cite web |url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=17&season=2016 |title=Mark Selby 2016/2017 |website=snooker.org |accessdate=5 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106015416/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=17&season=2016 |archive-date=6 January 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nHe then won 9\u20133 in another semi-final encounter with Bingham, to reach the final of the [[2016 International Championship|International Championship]] in Daqing, China, winning the event for the first time by overpowering Ding Junhui 10\u20131. Selby dominated their encounter, winning the last seven frames in a row, in the most one-sided ranking event final since the [[2012 World Open (snooker)|2012 Haikou World Open]] when [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] had defeated [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]] by the same scoreline. Selby made seven breaks over 50 while Ding managed a top run of just 47.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rkgsnooker.com/news/selby-dismissed-ding-in-daqing/news-36 |title=Selby Dismissed Ding in Daqing |year=2017 |website=RKG Snooker |accessdate=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221121329/https://www.rkgsnooker.com/news/selby-dismissed-ding-in-daqing/news-36 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a high quality quarter-final match lasting five hours against [[John Higgins]] at the [[2016 UK Championship|UK Championship]], Selby won 6\u20135 on the colours and then had a more routine 6\u20132 semi-final victory over [[Shaun Murphy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/dec/02/mark-selby-defeats-john-higgins-quarter-final-uk-championship |title=Mark Selby defeats John Higgins 6\u20135 after nail-biting deciding frame |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=2 December 2016 |agency=Press Association |accessdate=5 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308065016/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/dec/02/mark-selby-defeats-john-higgins-quarter-final-uk-championship |archive-date=8 March 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the final he had a 7\u20132 advantage over [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]], but it was reduced to 7\u20134, before four breaks of 130 or more were made in a span of five frames, two by each player. Selby then finished the match with a 107 break to win his second UK title and mean he has completed the Triple Crown twice in his career.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/38201842 |title=Mark Selby beats Ronnie O'Sullivan to win UK Championship final |date=4 December 2016 |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=4 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204184115/http://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/38201842 |archive-date=4 December 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nSelby could not get to a semi-final in the next seven tournaments, before winning through to the final of the [[2017 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] and he took the final three frames against [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] to claim his fourth ranking event title of the season 10\u20138.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/selby-king-beijing/ |title=Selby King in Beijing |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=2 April 2017 |accessdate=14 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403014509/http://www.worldsnooker.com/selby-king-beijing/ |archive-date=3 April 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNo one came close to Selby as he progressed through to the semi-finals of the [[2017 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], which included a 13\u20133 thrashing of [[Marco Fu]] in the quarter-finals with a session to spare. He next faced Ding Junhui who closed the gap to 16\u201315, after Selby had been 16\u201313 ahead. Selby won the 32nd frame to reach his third world final in four years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/selby-beats-ding-classic-semi-final/ |title=Selby Beats Ding in Classic Semi-final |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=29 April 2017 |accessdate=14 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502175113/http://www.worldsnooker.com/selby-beats-ding-classic-semi-final/ |archive-date=2 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Selby had an incredible run of winning 12 out of 14 frames after being 4\u201310 behind John Higgins and closed out the match 18\u201315 to win his third World Championship and become the fourth player after [[Steve Davis]], [[Stephen Hendry]] and Ronnie O'Sullivan to retain titles at the Crucible. He made a record \u00a3932,000 during the season. It was also Selby's fifth ranking title of the season after he had previously never won more than two titles in a campaign before. This tied him with Hendry and Ding as the only players to have won five ranking events in one season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/selby-conquers-crucible/ |title=Selby Conquers the Crucible Again |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=1 May 2017 |accessdate=2 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502060825/http://www.worldsnooker.com/selby-conquers-crucible/ |archive-date=2 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2017/2018===\nSelby started the [[2017\u201318 snooker season|season]] with a 3\u20135 defeat to eventual champion [[Neil Robertson]] in the first round of the [[2017 Hong Kong Masters|Hong Kong Masters]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/hong-kong-masters-2017/88696 |title=Hong Kong Masters snooker 2017: Draw, TV schedule, results & betting odds |date=23 July 2017 |work=Sporting Life |access-date=23 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223225328/https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/hong-kong-masters-2017/88696 |archive-date=23 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> His first ranking tournament of the season was the [[2017 China Championship (snooker)|China Championship]] where he was defeated 4\u20135 by [[Zhou Yuelong]] in the second round.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/zhou-upsets-selby-guangzhou/ |title=Zhou Upsets Selby In Guangzhou |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=18 August 2017 |accessdate=4 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205072700/http://www.worldsnooker.com/zhou-upsets-selby-guangzhou/ |archive-date=5 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He failed to progress past the fourth round of the [[2017 Paul Hunter Classic|Paul Hunter Classic]] in defence of his title, losing 1\u20134 to eventual champion [[Michael White (snooker player)|Michael White]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/41069526/ |title=Paul Hunter Classic 2017: Michael White beats Shaun Murphy in final |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=27 August 2017 |accessdate=4 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218085559/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/41069526 |archive-date=18 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was defeated 2\u20135 by [[Lee Walker]] in the first round of the [[2017 World Open (snooker)|World Open]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/41325497 |title=Mark Selby: World number one loses to Lee Walker at Yushan World Open |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=19 September 2017 |accessdate=4 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208035527/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/41325497 |archive-date=8 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> followed by a 2\u20134 defeat to [[Stuart Bingham]] in the quarter-finals of the [[2017 European Masters (snooker)|European Masters]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.com/snooker/european-masters/2017-2018/stuart-bingham-ousts-mark-selby-judd-trump-fends-off-mark-allen-fightback-to-make-semi-finals_sto6357828/story.shtml |title=Stuart Bingham ousts Mark Selby, Judd Trump fends off Mark Allen fightback to make semi-finals |work=[[Eurosport]] |date=6 October 2017 |accessdate=4 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205072824/https://www.eurosport.com/snooker/european-masters/2017-2018/stuart-bingham-ousts-mark-selby-judd-trump-fends-off-mark-allen-fightback-to-make-semi-finals_sto6357828/story.shtml |archive-date=5 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> and a third round exit at the [[2017 English Open (snooker)|English Open]] where he lost 1\u20134 to [[Xiao Guodong]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theoldgreenbaize.com/2017/10/19/english-open-blown-wide-open-as-mark-selby-suffers-surprise-defeat/ |title=English Open blown wide open as Mark Selby suffers surprise defeat |first=Nigel |last=Slater |date=19 October 2017 |website=The Old Green Baize |accessdate=4 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205072436/https://theoldgreenbaize.com/2017/10/19/english-open-blown-wide-open-as-mark-selby-suffers-surprise-defeat/ |archive-date=5 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSelby successfully defended his [[2017 International Championship|International Championship]] title in November, to claim his first ranking title of the season. After surviving a fightback from [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]], who trailed 3\u20138 and 7\u20139 in the final, Selby prevailed 10\u20137.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/41877821/ |title=International Championship: Mark Selby retains title by beating Mark Allen 10-7 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=5 November 2017 |accessdate=4 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171221075243/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/41877821 |archive-date=21 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/sport/other-sport/leicesters-mark-selby-back-winning-734868 |title=Leicester's Mark Selby back to winning ways with International Championship crown |date=6 November 2017 |first=Jon |last=Paul |website=[[Leicester Mercury|LeicestershireLive]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221140449/https://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/sport/other-sport/leicesters-mark-selby-back-winning-734868 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> As reigning World Snooker Champion, he qualified automatically for the [[2017 Champion of Champions]], but was defeated 4\u20136 in the quarter-finals by [[Luca Brecel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/champion-of-champions/2017-2018/luca-brecel-holds-nerve-to-stun-mark-selby-in-reaching-champion-of-champions-semi-finals_sto6403721/story.shtml |title=Luca Brecel holds nerve to stun Mark Selby in reaching Champion of Champions semi-finals |work=[[Eurosport]] |date=8 November 2017 |accessdate=4 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205130102/https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/champion-of-champions/2017-2018/luca-brecel-holds-nerve-to-stun-mark-selby-in-reaching-champion-of-champions-semi-finals_sto6403721/story.shtml |archive-date=5 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He suffered another quarter-final defeat at the [[2017 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]], losing 3\u20135 against 2011 finalist [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]]. Defending his title at the [[2017 UK Championship|UK Championship]], he was eliminated 3\u20136 by [[Scott Donaldson]] in the last 64.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/great-scott-floors-champ-selby/ |title=Great Scott Floors Champ Selby |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=2 December 2017 |accessdate=4 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204061259/http://www.worldsnooker.com/great-scott-floors-champ-selby/ |archive-date=4 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn January, he played Mark Willams in the first round of the [[2018 Masters (snooker)|Masters]], in a repeat of the [[2017 Masters (snooker)|previous year's event]], where Selby had won their first-round encounter 6\u20135. However, this time the finishing scoreline was reversed as Selby lost the deciding frame (only the second time he had done so at the Masters).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/42683553 |title=Masters: Mark Selby loses to Mark Williams in first round at Alexandra Palace |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=14 January 2018 |accessdate=4 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117094142/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/42683553 |archive-date=17 January 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He retained his [[2018 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] title in April, for his third in four years, defeating [[Barry Hawkins]] 11\u20133 in the final.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/selby-back-form-china-open-victory/ |title=Selby Back On Form With China Open Victory |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=8 April 2018 |accessdate=23 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412201558/http://www.worldsnooker.com/selby-back-form-china-open-victory/ |archive-date=12 April 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later that month, his two-year reign as World Champion ended in the first round of the [[2018 World Snooker Championship]], where he fell to [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]] 4\u201310, unable to recover from a 2\u20137 deficit in the first session. In winning the match, Perry became the first player to beat Selby at the World Championship since [[Anthony McGill]] had defeated him in the second round in [[2015 World Snooker Championship|2015]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/43848687 |title=World Snooker Championship 2018: Mark Selby beaten by Joe Perry in first round |date=21 April 2018 |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |work=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=23 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180421124226/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/43848687 |archive-date=21 April 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite this disappointment, Selby finished the season as world number one for the seventh year in a row.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n===2018/2019===\nSelby's first appearance of the [[2018\u201319 snooker season|2018\u201319 season]] was at the [[2018 World Open (snooker)|World Open]], where he reached the last 32, losing 4\u20135 to [[Noppon Saengkham]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/45128549 |title=World Open: Mark Selby loses to world number 53 Noppon Saengkham |date=9 August 2018 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129014007/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/45128549 |archive-date=29 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> His appearance in the [[2018 China Championship]] ended in victory, as he defeated [[John Higgins]] 10\u20139 in a very close-fought final.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wst.tv/selby-edges-higgins-in-guangzhou-thriller/ |title=Selby Edges Higgins in Guangzhou Thriller |date=30 September 2018 |work=World Snooker |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221072707/https://wst.tv/selby-edges-higgins-in-guangzhou-thriller/ |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, the later stages of the season were not as successful for Selby. His best run after the China Championship was the semi-final of the [[2018 Northern Ireland Open|Northern Ireland Open]], which he lost 5\u20136 to [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] on the final black.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/46248930 |title=Northern Ireland Open: Ronnie O'Sullivan beats Mark Selby on final black to reach final |date=17 November 2018 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811204826/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/46248930 |archive-date=11 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He suffered disappointments in other tournaments, including a surprising 3\u20136 loss to amateur [[James Cahill (snooker player)|James Cahill]] in the first round of the [[2018 UK Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/46394532 |title=UK Championship: Mark Selby beaten by amateur James Cahill in round one |date=30 November 2018 |first=Owen |last=Phillips |work=BBC Sport |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820190217/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/46394532 |archive-date=20 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the [[2019 Masters (snooker)|2019 Masters]], Selby lost 2\u20136 to eventual winner [[Judd Trump]] in the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/trump-seizes-the-initiative/157480 |title=Masters snooker 2019: Judd Trump beats Mark Selby 6-2 in quarter-final |date=19 January 2019 |work=Sporting Life |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226120042/https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/trump-seizes-the-initiative/157480 |archive-date=2020-02-26 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSelby qualified for all three [[2019 Coral Cup]] tournaments ([[2019 World Grand Prix|World Grand Prix]], [[2019 Players Championship (snooker)|Players Championship]] and [[2019 Tour Championship|Tour Championship]]), but did not progress past the quarter-finals in any of them. On 24 March, following Ronnie O'Sullivan's victory in the Tour Championship final, Selby lost his number one ranking to O'Sullivan,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/snooker-news-ronnie-osullivan-makes-astonishing-return-to-world-no-1-with-tour-championship-win_sto7199593/story.shtml |title=O'Sullivan completes astonishing return to world no 1 with Tour Championship victory |date=24 March 2019 |first=Desmond |last=Kane |work=Eurosport |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325114223/https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/snooker-news-ronnie-osullivan-makes-astonishing-return-to-world-no-1-with-tour-championship-win_sto7199593/story.shtml |archive-date=25 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> having held the position since February 2015. He had the chance to regain the top spot at the [[2019 China Open (snooker)|2019 China Open]], but lost 3\u20136 to [[Craig Steadman]] in the qualifying round, which was held over from the original qualification stage.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://asia.eurosport.com/snooker/china-open/2018-2019/mark-selby-defeat-confirms-ronnie-o-sullivan-as-world-no-1-for-world-championship_sto7210213/story.shtml |title=Selby defeat confirms O'Sullivan as world no 1 for World Championship |date=1 April 2019 |first=Kevin |last=Coulson |work=Eurosport Asia |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> At the [[2019 World Snooker Championship]], the Leicester player beat [[Zhao Xintong]] 10\u20137 in the first round before being defeated 10\u201313 by [[Gary Wilson (snooker player)|Gary Wilson]] in the second round.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wst.tv/wilson-completes-shock-win-over-selby/ |title=Wilson Completes Shock Win Over Selby |date=27 April 2019 |work=World Snooker |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220213234/https://wst.tv/wilson-completes-shock-win-over-selby/ |archive-date=20 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As a result, Selby ended the season ranked sixth, being overtaken by John Higgins, [[Neil Robertson]] and that year's world champion Judd Trump. This was the first time in eight years that Selby did not end the season as world number one.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n===2019/2020===\n\nAt the start of the season, Selby reached the semi-finals of the [[2019 International Championship|International Championship]], losing 4\u20139 to [[Judd Trump]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/international-championship/2019-2020/snooker-news-judd-trump-beats-mark-selby-to-reach-international-championship-final_sto7402404/story.shtml |title=Rampant Trump beats Selby to reach International Championship final |date=9 August 2019 |work=Eurosport |access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> and in defending his title at the [[2019 China Championship|China Championship]], he lost 3\u20136 to [[Shaun Murphy]], again in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wst.tv/murphy-into-guangzhou-final/ |title=Murphy into Guangzhou Final |date=28 September 2019 |work=World Snooker |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221053824/https://wst.tv/murphy-into-guangzhou-final/ |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> He achieved his first [[Home Nations Series]] victory in October 2019, defeating [[David Gilbert (snooker player)|David Gilbert]] 9\u20131 in the final of the [[2019 English Open (snooker)|English Open]] to win the Steve Davis Trophy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/50119006 |title=English Open: Mark Selby hammers David Gilbert 9\u20131 in final |date=20 October 2019 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211185653/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/50119006 |archive-date=11 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The following week, he lost 2\u20135 to [[Stuart Bingham]] in the last 16 of the [[2019 World Open (snooker)|World Open]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/bingham-thrives-trump-survives/173474 |title=World Open snooker day four review: Stuart Bingham impressive; John Higgins and Judd Trump scrape through |date=31 October 2019 |work=Sporting Life | |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226201534/https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/bingham-thrives-trump-survives/173474 |archive-date=2020-02-26 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[2019 Champion of Champions|Champion of Champions]], he fell short 2\u20136 to [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] in the group final.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/50310115 |title=Champion of Champions: Mark Allen beats Mark Selby 6\u20132 to reach semi-finals |date=5 November 2019 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226200030/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/50310115 |archive-date=2020-02-26 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSelby's ambition of winning all four Home Nations titles and a \u00a31,000,000 bonus  ended in the quarter-finals of the [[2019 Northern Ireland Open|Northern Ireland Open]], where he was defeated 4\u20135 by [[John Higgins]] after recovering from 1\u20134 down.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/higgins-pips-selby-ronnie-through/174098 |title=Northern Ireland Open: John Higgins beats Mark Selby; Judd Trump and Ronnie O'Sullivan through |date=15 November 2019 |work=Sporting Life |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226200032/https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/higgins-pips-selby-ronnie-through/174098 |archive-date=2020-02-26 |url-status=live}}</ref> He took more than six minutes to play a shot at one point during the seventh frame of this match, leading to criticism from the Eurosport commentator [[Neal Foulds]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/northern-ireland-open/2019-2020/snooker-news-mark-selby-takes-six-minutes-and-13-seconds-to-take-shot_sto7538910/story.shtml |title='It's stupid' \u2013 Disbelief as Selby takes six minutes and 13 seconds to take shot |first=Ben |last=Snowball |date=15 November 2019 |website=Eurosport UK |access-date=16 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116045034/https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/northern-ireland-open/2019-2020/snooker-news-mark-selby-takes-six-minutes-and-13-seconds-to-take-shot_sto7538910/story.shtml |archive-date=16 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He won the [[2019 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]] in December, beating [[Jack Lisowski]] 9\u20136 in the final to pick up the Stephen Hendry Trophy. Having also won the English Open earlier in the season, he became the first player to win more than one tournament in the Home Nations Series in a single season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/selby-seals-scottish-open-title/175183 |title=Scottish Open snooker: Mark Selby beats Jack Lisowski 9\u20136 in Glasgow final |date=16 December 2019 |work=Sporting Life |agency=Press Association |access-date=26 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191217095819/https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/selby-seals-scottish-open-title/175183 |archive-date=17 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, he started with a few unremarkable performances. He lost in the first round of the [[2020 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] against [[Ali Carter]] in January,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2020/0112/1106011-carter-dumps-out-selby-in-first-round-of-masters/ |title=Carter dumps out Selby in first round of Masters |date=2020-01-13 |website=[[RT\u00c9.ie]] |access-date=2020-02-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113170540/https://www.rte.ie/sport/snooker/2020/0112/1106011-carter-dumps-out-selby-in-first-round-of-masters/ |archive-date=2020-01-13 |url-status=live}}</ref> and failed to qualify at the [[2020 German Masters|German Masters]] later the same month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?event=859 |title=BetVictor German Masters (2020) |website=snooker.org |access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> At the [[2020 European Masters|European Masters]], he lost in the second round to [[Barry Hawkins]]; after losing the first four frames, he staged a comeback to level at 4\u20134 but then lost the deciding frame.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/european-masters/2019-2020/snooker-news-big-names-tumble-at-european-masters-as-ding-williams-and-higgins-are-eliminated_sto7627407/story.shtml |title=Big names tumble at European Masters as Selby, Ding, Williams and Higgins are eliminated |date=2020-01-23 |first=Enis |last=Koylu |work=Eurosport |access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> He qualified for the [[2020 World Grand Prix|World Grand Prix]], where he lost 3\u20134 to [[Xiao Guodong]] in the first round despite making two centuries.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nIn February, Selby reached the quarter-final stage of the last Home Nations event, the [[2020 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], where he was defeated 1\u20135 by [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/51505570 |title=Welsh Open: Ronnie O'Sullivan eases into semi-finals |date=2020-02-14 |work=BBC Sport |access-date=2020-03-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329022616/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/51505570 |archive-date=2020-03-29 |url-status=live}}</ref> He also qualified for the [[2020 Players Championship (snooker)|Players Championship]], based on the one-year ranking list; in the first round, he whitewashed [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] 6\u20130,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/selby-soars-in-southport/177665 |title=Snooker results: Mark Selby beats Mark Williams 6-0 in Coral Players Championship |date=2020-02-24 |work=Sporting Life |access-date=2020-03-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328184102/https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/selby-soars-in-southport/177665 |archive-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live}}</ref> but was then knocked out in the quarter-finals by [[Stephen Maguire]] in a deciding frame 5\u20136.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/maguire-holds-off-selby-comeback/177777 |title=Snooker results: Stephen Maguire beats Mark Selby in Players Championship |first=Richard |last=Mann |date=2020-02-28 |work=Sporting Life |access-date=2020-03-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328184059/https://www.sportinglife.com/snooker/news/maguire-holds-off-selby-comeback/177777 |archive-date=2020-03-28 |url-status=live}}</ref> In March, he also participated at the [[2020 Gibraltar Open|Gibraltar Open]], but was eliminated in the third round by [[Lyu Haotian]] 1\u20134.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/gibraltar-open/2019-2020/snooker-news-mark-selby-and-stuart-bingham-suffer-defeats-at-gibraltar-open_sto7703817/story.shtml |title=Selby and Bingham suffer defeats at Gibraltar Open |date=2020-03-14 |work=Eurosport |access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Pool career==\nIn addition to snooker, Selby is also an adept [[pool (cue sports)|pool]] player \u2013 specifically [[Blackball (pool)|blackball]] and [[Chinese eight-ball]]. In July 2006, he won the [[World Eight-ball Pool Federation|WEPF]] [[List of world eight-ball champions|World Eight-ball Championship]], beating [[Darren Appleton]] 11\u20137 in the final at [[Blackpool]].<ref name=uk8ball1>{{cite web |url=http://www.uk8ball.com/article.php?sid=2469 |title=Selby pockets world rules pool crown |accessdate=6 May 2007 |publisher=UK 8 Ball Pool Community, 17 June 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061206035403/http://www.uk8ball.com/article.php?sid=2469 |archivedate=6 December 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref> On 2 February 2015, Selby played in the {{ill|2015 Chinese Pool World Championship|de|Chinese 8-Ball World Championship 2015}}, but lost to [[Darren Appleton]] 19\u201321 in the final.<ref name=\"Ashdown\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://thepoolscene.com/international-pool-and-billiards/darren-appleton-bai-ge-won-first-china-pool-champion |title=Darren Appleton and Bai Ge Won the First China Pool Champion |date=13 February 2015 |first=Alison |last=Chang |website=The Pool Scene |access-date=30 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505234346/http://thepoolscene.com/international-pool-and-billiards/darren-appleton-bai-ge-won-first-china-pool-champion |archive-date=5 May 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pAaL7ZERSxA |title=Mark Selby v Darren Appleton, Final 2015 Chinese Pool World Championship |via=YouTube |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114160552/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pAaL7ZERSxA |archivedate=14 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSelby is a fan of [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], whom he has supported since childhood.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lcfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/LatestNews/0,,10274~1127784,00.html |title=Mark Selby Picture Special |date=4 October 2007 |website=lcfc.premiumtv.co.uk |publisher=[[Leicester City F.C.]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071216063407/https://www.lcfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/LatestNews/0,,10274~1127784,00.html |archive-date=16 December 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> His 2014 World Championship victory came on the same day as City celebrated [[2013\u201314 Football League Championship|their promotion]] to the [[Premier League]] with an open-top bus parade, while his 2016 World Championship victory came on 2 May 2016, which he won just 11 minutes after the team sealed their first Premier League title.<ref name=\"2016 WC\"/> He is a fan of darts, beating [[Eric Bristow]] in an exhibition leg of 301 in 2007, and taking on [[Raymond van Barneveld]] in exhibition matches.<ref>{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Bozeat |title=Selby Hits Top Form .... but on the Oche! |url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-171983186 |work=Sunday Mercury |location=Birmingham, England |date=2 December 2007 |accessdate=17 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Darts: Selby on the oche |url=https://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/news/Darts-Selby-oche/article-944870-detail/article.html |work=Leicester Mercury |date=29 April 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100121094632/https://www.thisisleicestershire.co.uk/news/Darts-Selby-oche/article-944870-detail/article.html |archive-date=21 January 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSelby's wife Vikki Layton, who often attends his major matches, is a former Irish international pool player born in [[Ipswich]].<ref name=\"Troughten2014\">{{cite web |first=Adrian |last=Troughton |title=World snooker champion Mark Selby in the frame to become a father |url=https://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/World-snooker-champion-Mark-Selby-frame-father/story-21093918-detail/story.html |work=[[Leicester Mercury]] |date=14 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515030741/https://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/World-snooker-champion-Mark-Selby-frame-father/story-21093918-detail/story.html |archive-date=15 May 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> They announced their engagement in August 2010,<ref>{{cite web |title=Mark And Vikki To Tie The Knot |url=https://www.worldsnooker.com/news(Mark_And_Vikki_To_Tie_The_Knot)-2516.htm |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=22 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100822171731/https://www.worldsnooker.com/news(Mark_And_Vikki_To_Tie_The_Knot)-2516.htm |archive-date=22 August 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and were married in [[Mexico]] on 24 May 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mark And Vikki Tie The Knot |url=https://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2369233,00.html |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=31 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110603085750/https://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2369233,00.html |archive-date=3 June 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Their daughter Sofia was born in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mark Selby Becomes A Dad |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~4291898,00.html |work=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |date=11 November 2014 |accessdate=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111183910/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~4291898,00.html |archive-date=11 November 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> They have a swimming pool at their home in Leicester, although Selby himself is a non-swimmer.<ref name=RTE2014 />\n\nSelby's [[List of snooker player nicknames|nickname]], \"The Jester from Leicester\", was given to him by snooker [[Master of ceremonies|compere]] Richard Beare.<ref name=\"Ashdown\">{{cite web |first=John |last=Ashdown |title=Small talk: Mark Selby |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/apr/18/sportinterviews.worldsnookerchampionship |work=The Guardian |date=18 April 2008 |accessdate=17 January 2010 |quote=Well, I just seem to make people laugh. I used to have a laugh and a joke with the compere, Richard Beare, and he gave me the nickname the Jester from Leicester. |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002205104/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/apr/18/sportinterviews.worldsnookerchampionship |archive-date=2 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\nBelow is a list of competition results for professional seasons starting from 1999.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Mark Selby|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=17|publisher=snooker.org|accessdate=3 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104040745/http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=17|archive-date=4 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! Tournament\n! [[Snooker season 1999/2000|1999/<br />00]]\n! [[Snooker season 2000/2001|2000/<br />01]]\n! [[Snooker season 2001/2002|2001/<br />02]]\n! [[Snooker season 2002/2003|2002/<br />03]]\n! [[Snooker season 2003/2004|2003/<br />04]]\n! [[Snooker season 2004/2005|2004/<br />05]]\n! [[Snooker season 2005/2006|2005/<br />06]]\n! [[Snooker season 2006/2007|2006/<br />07]]\n! [[Snooker season 2007/2008|2007/<br />08]]\n! [[Snooker season 2008/2009|2008/<br />09]]\n! [[Snooker season 2009/2010|2009/<br />10]]\n! [[Snooker season 2010/2011|2010/<br />11]]\n! [[Snooker season 2011/2012|2011/<br />12]]\n! [[Snooker season 2012/2013|2012/<br />13]]\n! [[Snooker season 2013/2014|2013/<br />14]]\n! [[Snooker season 2014/2015|2014/<br />15]]\n! [[Snooker season 2015/2016|2015/<br />16]]\n! [[Snooker season 2016/2017|2016/<br />17]]\n! [[Snooker season 2017/2018|2017/<br />18]]\n! [[Snooker season 2018/2019|2018/<br />19]]\n! [[Snooker season 2019/2020|2019/<br />20]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]]<ref name=\"Ranking history\">{{cite web |title=Ranking History |url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp |publisher=Snooker.org |accessdate=6 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219070820/http://www.snooker.org/Rnk/history.asp |archive-date=19 December 2